WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:04.830
As we recover from Senior Week
and sit down with our family

00:00:04.830 --> 00:00:07.340
and friends from
home, this question

00:00:07.340 --> 00:00:12.070
will come up over dinner and in
many situations in the future.

00:00:12.070 --> 00:00:16.750
So, what did you
learn at Harvard?

00:00:16.750 --> 00:00:18.450
What will you tell them?

00:00:18.450 --> 00:00:22.920
What has our Harvard
education really been?

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:26.080
Our Harvard education.

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:29.100
It could have been
discovered in our passions,

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:31.890
realizing disciplines
that we'd never

00:00:31.890 --> 00:00:35.230
heard of before coming to
college, extracurriculars

00:00:35.230 --> 00:00:36.860
that we somehow
ended up spending

00:00:36.860 --> 00:00:40.370
hours on without realization.

00:00:40.370 --> 00:00:43.060
Our Harvard education.

00:00:43.060 --> 00:00:47.080
Perhaps it was the realization
that when a friend strikes up

00:00:47.080 --> 00:00:49.680
a meaningful, late
night conversation,

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:52.980
that paper or problem
set could wait.

00:00:52.980 --> 00:00:56.320
Or learning the importance
of thinking of a friend

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:59.090
and stopping by their
room just to check in

00:00:59.090 --> 00:01:01.820
and see how they were doing.

00:01:01.820 --> 00:01:04.349
Our Harvard education.

00:01:04.349 --> 00:01:08.490
Oftentimes, it may have been
failing and dusting ourselves

00:01:08.490 --> 00:01:14.240
off and getting back up and
facing everything again.

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:16.770
Our Harvard education.

00:01:16.770 --> 00:01:20.390
Maybe it was realizing that we
were not content simply being

00:01:20.390 --> 00:01:23.230
a product of Harvard,
that we wanted Harvard

00:01:23.230 --> 00:01:26.680
to be a product of us, that
we wanted to do something

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:29.760
so that we could look back
at our college and say,

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:33.870
this is an institution
that better reflects me

00:01:33.870 --> 00:01:39.320
and the values I hold dear
because of my efforts.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:42.040
Our Harvard education.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:45.260
It could be about becoming
more comfortable with being

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:50.110
uncomfortable, with inevitable
uncertainty, steadfast turmoil

00:01:50.110 --> 00:01:52.260
in constant flux.

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:54.330
Our Harvard education
could have been

00:01:54.330 --> 00:01:58.080
about taking risks, embracing
our fear of the unknown

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:02.690
and moving forward despite of
it, and taking deep breaths

00:02:02.690 --> 00:02:06.090
and making decisions to change
our lives when we weren't

00:02:06.090 --> 00:02:09.630
living the realities
that we wanted.

00:02:09.630 --> 00:02:14.750
So, what did our time
at Harvard teach us?

00:02:14.750 --> 00:02:18.950
How will it help as we go
forth into the real world?

00:02:18.950 --> 00:02:23.010
We may not have all the
answers now, and that's OK.

00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:27.250
We don't and can't know now
everything that we have learned

00:02:27.250 --> 00:02:31.550
and all the ways in which we
have changed here at Harvard.

00:02:31.550 --> 00:02:36.530
That ceremony we have tomorrow,
commencement, means beginning.

00:02:36.530 --> 00:02:39.870
We are just getting started.

00:02:39.870 --> 00:02:42.940
And as we go forth
from Dexter Gate,

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:46.880
having hopefully grown in
wisdom and soon departing

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:50.540
to better serve thy
country and thy kind,

00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:54.300
I hope that we stay
true to ourselves.

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:59.010
It has taken us so much courage
and grit to grow up and become

00:02:59.010 --> 00:03:02.410
who we are during the
challenging and incredible

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:05.800
experience that
Harvard has been.

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:08.670
With each decision that
we make with our hearts,

00:03:08.670 --> 00:03:13.360
our compass is tweaked a
little here, a little there,

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:18.140
to ultimately land each of us in
the spot that is right for us.

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:21.774
Thank you so much class of
2014, and congratulations.

00:03:21.774 --> 00:03:24.618
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:31.400
Thanks Jen.

00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:34.236
My name is Arjun Modi, a proud
resident of Kirkland House,

00:03:34.236 --> 00:03:35.485
and I am your class treasurer.

00:03:35.485 --> 00:03:37.710
[CHEERING]

00:03:37.710 --> 00:03:40.260
I'm Rainjade Chung, and I
represent Kirkland House

00:03:40.260 --> 00:03:41.520
on the senior class committee.

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:44.490
[CHEERING]

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:47.810
It is our great pleasure
to introduce to you today

00:03:47.810 --> 00:03:50.950
a man who holds a special
place in all of our hearts.

00:03:50.950 --> 00:03:53.450
The one and only, Dean Pfister.

00:03:53.450 --> 00:03:56.270
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:03.000
Dean Pfister is the Asa Gray
professor of Systematic Botany,

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.440
and his love of plants,
trees, flowers, and fungi

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:08.980
is known all too
well by most of us.

00:04:08.980 --> 00:04:12.960
Dean Pfister joined Harvard
40 years ago in 1974.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:14.820
Since then he has been
intimately involved

00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:16.440
in undergraduate life.

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:20.230
In 1982, he assumed a role
special to myself and Rainjade

00:04:20.230 --> 00:04:22.110
when he became comaster
of Kirkland House,

00:04:22.110 --> 00:04:24.920
serving for 18 years
with his wife Kathleen.

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:27.470
Most recently he was Dean
of Harvard summer school

00:04:27.470 --> 00:04:28.875
before leaving
that post to serve

00:04:28.875 --> 00:04:32.580
as interim dean of the
College this past year.

00:04:32.580 --> 00:04:34.900
And what a year it has been.

00:04:34.900 --> 00:04:37.370
In a message to the class
declaring that we already

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:40.280
beat Yale, the weekend
before the game,

00:04:40.280 --> 00:04:43.580
he reminded us that Harvard
is home to the world's largest

00:04:43.580 --> 00:04:46.930
university owned herbarium
with more than five

00:04:46.930 --> 00:04:50.196
million specimens
to Yale's 350,000.

00:04:50.196 --> 00:04:51.634
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:51.634 --> 00:04:53.622
[CHEERING AND APPLAUSE]

00:04:57.610 --> 00:05:00.400
Because of this he said
that Yale could not even

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:03.020
compete with us,
a premonition that

00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:06.892
was confirmed when we
won the game 34 to seven.

00:05:06.892 --> 00:05:10.780
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:13.360
From sharing his reading list
with the class, which often

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:16.900
consists of mystery novels
such as How the Light Gets In,

00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:20.510
a Chief Inspector Gamache novel,
to helping us identify fungi

00:05:20.510 --> 00:05:23.120
around Harvard
Yard, to reminding

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:25.190
us to take care of
ourselves and others

00:05:25.190 --> 00:05:28.420
amidst difficult times on
campus and off, Dean Pfister

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:31.560
has undeniably been a
source of comfort, support,

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:32.940
and many a laugh.

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:34.590
He has brought us
cupcakes in Lamont,

00:05:34.590 --> 00:05:36.980
traveled with us to
class on the shuttle,

00:05:36.980 --> 00:05:39.270
and helped us welcome
freshman to their new homes

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:41.660
on housing day.

00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:45.670
Dean Pfister, you will be missed
by the undergraduate community,

00:05:45.670 --> 00:05:48.770
and we wish you all the
best in your next adventure.

00:05:48.770 --> 00:05:51.510
Please join us in a warm round
of applause for Dean Pfister.

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:55.920
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:56.890
Thank you.

00:05:56.890 --> 00:05:57.390
Thank you.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:07.950
Thank you.

00:06:07.950 --> 00:06:10.260
This is wonderful.

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:16.200
Greetings and congratulations
to the class of 2014.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:21.570
My congratulations are not only
to the remarkable women and men

00:06:21.570 --> 00:06:24.670
who will march tomorrow
toward their future,

00:06:24.670 --> 00:06:28.850
but also parents and friends who
have made the journey possible.

00:06:28.850 --> 00:06:31.980
Thank you too.

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:38.890
At last, I have you all here
in my extended classroom.

00:06:38.890 --> 00:06:43.240
Please pay very close
attention because tomorrow we

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:46.950
pass out the exams.

00:06:46.950 --> 00:06:50.660
Allow me to review the syllabus.

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:54.530
Look over toward
University Hall here,

00:06:54.530 --> 00:06:58.490
a single pine stands there.

00:06:58.490 --> 00:07:01.740
Its predecessor,
also a white pine,

00:07:01.740 --> 00:07:04.240
was blown down in one
of the hurricanes that

00:07:04.240 --> 00:07:07.050
occurred in the 1980s.

00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:09.570
Originally, a row
of pines marked

00:07:09.570 --> 00:07:16.620
a special spot, the site in
times before indoor plumbing,

00:07:16.620 --> 00:07:18.172
of the college outhouse.

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:24.160
Such an essential place.

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:27.020
So full of history--

00:07:27.020 --> 00:07:30.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:33.995
--that marks the spot where
we celebrate our last days

00:07:33.995 --> 00:07:34.495
together.

00:07:39.290 --> 00:07:43.720
Time flows on, things change.

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:48.300
Just as Harvard has changed
over time, so have you.

00:07:48.300 --> 00:07:52.540
During this interim year, I
have had the singular pleasure

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:57.490
and honor of greeting a freshman
class whose graduation I will

00:07:57.490 --> 00:08:01.900
not oversee, and
celebrating today

00:08:01.900 --> 00:08:09.010
and all year a senior class that
I did not welcome as freshmen.

00:08:09.010 --> 00:08:12.030
We have all been on a journey.

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:15.200
Yours has been one
of concentrations

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:19.780
and requirements,
performances, competitions,

00:08:19.780 --> 00:08:23.460
high points, low points.

00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:28.160
Well, mine has been
characterized by what?

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:30.590
Perhaps I could
summarize it a bit

00:08:30.590 --> 00:08:33.760
as learning about the
complicated ecosystem

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:37.350
of academic administration.

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:40.940
And more importantly,
following you all

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:44.870
in your final
undergraduate year.

00:08:44.870 --> 00:08:48.810
In The Fellowship of the
Rings, J.R.R. Tolkien wrote,

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:52.850
"Not all those who
wander are lost."

00:08:52.850 --> 00:08:55.700
Facing the challenges
in our journey,

00:08:55.700 --> 00:09:00.920
I suspect that all of us
have felt at times lost.

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:03.830
But now in retrospect,
I think we may just

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:05.535
be wandering quite a bit.

00:09:08.230 --> 00:09:11.340
When I talked to freshman
at convocation in September,

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:15.170
I reflected on my
early academic journey.

00:09:15.170 --> 00:09:18.590
How I grew up in Ohio,
that my sister and I

00:09:18.590 --> 00:09:21.990
were the first in our
family to attend college,

00:09:21.990 --> 00:09:25.870
that I went to Miami University,
the real Miami University

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:26.830
in Oxford, Ohio.

00:09:29.770 --> 00:09:35.500
Looking back, I must
confess that I was clueless.

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:39.740
Perhaps when you review
your first year now

00:09:39.740 --> 00:09:42.820
you'll get the same sense.

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:46.850
I was a small town kid
on a pretty small campus,

00:09:46.850 --> 00:09:51.250
inadequately prepared to cope.

00:09:51.250 --> 00:09:54.580
Despite my rough start, I
discovered an academic field

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:58.470
and a set of mentors
who saved me.

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:03.260
By telling the freshman about
my initial college difficulties,

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:07.710
I hope to encourage them to
reach out, extend themselves

00:10:07.710 --> 00:10:11.070
to find what would
compel and inspire them.

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:15.330
Today my point in telling you
about my undergraduate trials

00:10:15.330 --> 00:10:18.200
is that you and I share
an important aspect

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:19.650
of our journey.

00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:22.250
We succeeded.

00:10:22.250 --> 00:10:25.920
Henry Ward Beecher wrote,
"We should not judge people

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:29.370
by their peak of excellence,
but by the distance

00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:33.490
they have traveled from the
point where they started."

00:10:33.490 --> 00:10:37.010
Personally, I find
these words reassuring.

00:10:37.010 --> 00:10:40.700
You may also find them
worth remembering.

00:10:40.700 --> 00:10:42.540
So here we are.

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:48.610
We have traveled to the very,
very eve of commencement.

00:10:48.610 --> 00:10:52.300
It may interest you in the early
days of Harvard-- Jen stole

00:10:52.300 --> 00:10:56.090
some of this from
me-- commencement

00:10:56.090 --> 00:11:00.590
came not at this point in time
of the year, but in the fall

00:11:00.590 --> 00:11:02.395
after a summer break.

00:11:02.395 --> 00:11:06.490
It came when the year was
commencing, a beginning.

00:11:06.490 --> 00:11:11.220
In the spring there was another
type of celebration, Class Day.

00:11:11.220 --> 00:11:14.070
Class Day was the
last day of term.

00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:16.920
In the 1830s, seniors
met in the morning

00:11:16.920 --> 00:11:21.330
in one of the common
rooms in University Hall.

00:11:21.330 --> 00:11:23.260
There they had a
religious service

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:25.940
conducted by one of
their own before marching

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:28.630
in procession two
Wadsworth House where

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:30.560
the president lived.

00:11:30.560 --> 00:11:34.810
The seniors then escorted the
president to Holden Chapel

00:11:34.810 --> 00:11:37.650
where there were
prayers, orations, poems,

00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:41.710
a class ode, most in Latin.

00:11:41.710 --> 00:11:44.740
Later a new set of customs
that included dancing

00:11:44.740 --> 00:11:48.640
around the Liberty Tree
and Elm near Holden Chapel.

00:11:51.600 --> 00:11:54.560
On those occasions,
as one writer

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:59.450
noted, "The seniors provided
punch in a barrel and brandy

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:04.650
and water in pails which were
placed at the foot of the tree

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:08.410
and were steadily
replenished all afternoon,

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:11.810
mugs being provided
for all comers.

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:14.990
There was singing and
dancing, speaking,

00:12:14.990 --> 00:12:18.670
intermingled with
unlimited drinking.

00:12:18.670 --> 00:12:20.940
Not the slightest
attempt was made

00:12:20.940 --> 00:12:23.870
to control or repress this.

00:12:23.870 --> 00:12:27.185
It was simply a brutal
hallowing orgy."

00:12:27.185 --> 00:12:30.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:30.130 --> 00:12:32.020
"There was little
attempt at fun,

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:35.360
no kind of system of
traditional order.

00:12:35.360 --> 00:12:42.310
Nothing but steady drinking
and the resulting drunkenness."

00:12:42.310 --> 00:12:49.190
Now a few of you think, perhaps,
that you invented everything

00:12:49.190 --> 00:12:50.067
anew.

00:12:50.067 --> 00:12:53.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:56.570
The tree is long
gone, killed by elm

00:12:56.570 --> 00:13:01.060
disease early in
the last century.

00:13:01.060 --> 00:13:03.450
But Class Day spirit lives on.

00:13:03.450 --> 00:13:06.185
Now the celebration of
commencement and class day

00:13:06.185 --> 00:13:07.900
have merged and changed.

00:13:07.900 --> 00:13:14.710
Today and tomorrow you have
orations, singing, and pomp.

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:19.330
Maybe not so many barrels of
booze around, though I'm always

00:13:19.330 --> 00:13:22.120
surprised and grateful
to note the grounds crew

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:25.775
has managed to collect all
the discarded bottles and cans

00:13:25.775 --> 00:13:29.000
and cups before the
arrival of your guests

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.410
on commencement morning.

00:13:32.410 --> 00:13:35.530
Still, our language of
commencement beginning

00:13:35.530 --> 00:13:37.260
carries on.

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:40.940
For you this is another
sort of beginning.

00:13:40.940 --> 00:13:43.450
So let me tell you
what to expect tomorrow

00:13:43.450 --> 00:13:46.230
regarding the venerable
exercises here

00:13:46.230 --> 00:13:51.300
in Tercentenary Theatre
and your role in them.

00:13:51.300 --> 00:13:53.370
During the
commencement exercises,

00:13:53.370 --> 00:13:55.320
the president will
confer degrees

00:13:55.320 --> 00:13:57.930
upon the university's graduates.

00:13:57.930 --> 00:14:01.840
First Ph.D. and Master's
degrees are called.

00:14:01.840 --> 00:14:04.790
Then the professional
schools will

00:14:04.790 --> 00:14:09.000
be acknowledged in the reverse
order of their founding.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.990
Each of the schools has
its own little cheers

00:14:12.990 --> 00:14:19.140
and its members will wave about
their special little props.

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:22.280
Then last, the
college is called.

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:26.770
That gives us a chance
to outdo them all.

00:14:26.770 --> 00:14:29.240
When you are recognized,
it's your moment

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:32.120
to inform the graduate
and professional school

00:14:32.120 --> 00:14:36.340
students about which school
is the true jewel in Harvard's

00:14:36.340 --> 00:14:38.520
crown.

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:43.120
I hope you will seize the
day and out-cheer them all.

00:14:43.120 --> 00:14:45.000
Make sure that
those cheers can be

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.440
heard all the way to Somerville.

00:14:48.440 --> 00:14:53.530
And then when you quiet down
I will begin the salutation.

00:14:53.530 --> 00:14:57.500
Madame President and Fellows
of Harvard College, this

00:14:57.500 --> 00:15:01.010
refers to Drew Faust in
the Fellows of the Harvard

00:15:01.010 --> 00:15:02.680
Corporation.

00:15:02.680 --> 00:15:08.300
They form the legal entity
that is Harvard University.

00:15:08.300 --> 00:15:11.690
Next I will greet Mr.
President and members

00:15:11.690 --> 00:15:13.550
of the board of overseers.

00:15:13.550 --> 00:15:16.300
This refers to the
second governing body

00:15:16.300 --> 00:15:18.590
of our university
and its presidents.

00:15:21.100 --> 00:15:23.490
After these salutations
I will attest

00:15:23.490 --> 00:15:26.210
that you have fulfilled
the faculty's requirements

00:15:26.210 --> 00:15:30.340
for the first degree
in arts and sciences.

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:34.400
At that point right
there is no going back.

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:37.670
We've given away your room.

00:15:37.670 --> 00:15:41.000
Much as we love you, we
have opened the doors

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.210
to a new class.

00:15:43.210 --> 00:15:46.260
Like Adam and Eve,
you're cast out.

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:49.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:54.270
You have gone to the other side.

00:15:54.270 --> 00:15:58.280
Finally, I will pronounce
that each candidate stands

00:15:58.280 --> 00:16:03.040
ready to advance knowledge,
to promote understanding,

00:16:03.040 --> 00:16:06.400
and to serve society.

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:10.950
To advance knowledge, to
promote understanding,

00:16:10.950 --> 00:16:13.650
to serve society.

00:16:13.650 --> 00:16:17.550
Such a noble affirmation.

00:16:17.550 --> 00:16:20.770
But the fact is we leave
a lot to your imagination

00:16:20.770 --> 00:16:25.800
and ingenuity about what
those noble words mean.

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:28.180
Fortunately during
your time at Harvard,

00:16:28.180 --> 00:16:30.800
you have all been
engaged in these goals,

00:16:30.800 --> 00:16:33.840
whether you liked it or not.

00:16:33.840 --> 00:16:36.890
What we are certifying
and my deepest hope

00:16:36.890 --> 00:16:40.000
is that as you go
out from Harvard,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:45.360
you will indeed advance,
promote, and serve.

00:16:45.360 --> 00:16:49.250
It is what we expect of
you, whether in education,

00:16:49.250 --> 00:16:53.740
in business, in
professions, in life.

00:16:53.740 --> 00:16:55.830
Are these obligations?

00:16:55.830 --> 00:16:58.750
Yes, they are responsibilities.

00:16:58.750 --> 00:17:02.170
But this is what we
expect of ourselves

00:17:02.170 --> 00:17:07.490
and for our fellow inhabitants
of the small planet.

00:17:07.490 --> 00:17:09.819
One of my favorite
spots in Harvard Yard

00:17:09.819 --> 00:17:14.670
is behind Holden Chapel
toward Massachusetts Avenue.

00:17:14.670 --> 00:17:17.359
The chapel was built
to face the street.

00:17:17.359 --> 00:17:23.310
And this outward facing part is
the fancy side of the building.

00:17:23.310 --> 00:17:27.940
It is near the spot that
the class tree stood.

00:17:27.940 --> 00:17:30.200
You will find a sundial there.

00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:32.880
Many of you may have
already found that.

00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:37.500
Inscribed around the
support are the words,

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:42.960
"On this moment hangs eternity."

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:46.240
Keep this in mind tomorrow
when you celebrate.

00:17:46.240 --> 00:17:50.790
On this moment hangs eternity.

00:17:50.790 --> 00:17:53.520
You need to make the
best of the moment.

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:56.130
It leads us forward.

00:17:56.130 --> 00:18:01.185
What we do and decide now
is with us to eternity.

00:18:03.750 --> 00:18:07.670
Meanwhile, we are
here now, closing

00:18:07.670 --> 00:18:13.290
in on these last moments under
this magnificent green but wet

00:18:13.290 --> 00:18:13.790
canopy.

00:18:16.840 --> 00:18:20.110
I have enjoyed and valued our
time together immeasurably.

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:26.530
There were many performances
by various groups-- the Harvard

00:18:26.530 --> 00:18:32.900
Pops, Din &amp; Tonics, I, Too,
Am Harvard-- visits to houses,

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:36.660
and the senior scavenger hunt.

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:39.880
When it looked like you
could use a cupcake,

00:18:39.880 --> 00:18:43.320
I was glad you bring it to you.

00:18:43.320 --> 00:18:47.100
It pleased me to see so many
students in my office hours

00:18:47.100 --> 00:18:50.890
to discuss concerns
or just to say hello.

00:18:50.890 --> 00:18:53.670
Riding the shuttle bus
on a winter's morning

00:18:53.670 --> 00:18:55.990
allowed me to chat
with some of you

00:18:55.990 --> 00:19:00.060
and gave me a sense of what you
were doing in order to juggle

00:19:00.060 --> 00:19:04.940
classes, activities, athletics.

00:19:04.940 --> 00:19:08.110
And of course there
were the emails.

00:19:08.110 --> 00:19:12.650
For many of you my periodic
messages were informative.

00:19:12.650 --> 00:19:14.810
If they made you
smile and brought

00:19:14.810 --> 00:19:19.500
you a bit closer to this
marvelous community,

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:21.860
well, that was perhaps
most important.

00:19:26.490 --> 00:19:29.800
The last few days are your days.

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:32.870
Amid the hustle and bustle,
please spend a moment

00:19:32.870 --> 00:19:36.970
to reflect on what
you have done,

00:19:36.970 --> 00:19:44.210
the races run, lost, and won,
the perspectives examined,

00:19:44.210 --> 00:19:49.030
the minds changed-- yours,
and perhaps your parents--

00:19:49.030 --> 00:19:52.470
papers written, problems solved.

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:55.610
Bear in mind that with luck
and health, those friends

00:19:55.610 --> 00:19:59.280
you hold dear today
will come to join

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:04.500
you sharing the fifth,
10th, 25th, reunions.

00:20:04.500 --> 00:20:06.920
Much has happened
in these four years.

00:20:06.920 --> 00:20:08.670
Much has changed.

00:20:08.670 --> 00:20:12.750
There is a saying, no one ever
steps in the same river twice,

00:20:12.750 --> 00:20:18.310
for it is not the same river,
and it's not the same person,

00:20:18.310 --> 00:20:21.970
though you cannot step back
into the same Harvard we have

00:20:21.970 --> 00:20:29.740
shared, this Harvard, you and
I, in the same river together.

00:20:29.740 --> 00:20:32.100
I'm proud of you.

00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:36.460
I will close with the first
lines of Tolkien's poem.

00:20:36.460 --> 00:20:38.880
It's a riddle, really.

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:42.750
"All that is gold
does not glitter.

00:20:42.750 --> 00:20:47.220
Not all those who
wander are lost."

00:20:47.220 --> 00:20:53.370
May you, the graduates, find
the gold that does not glitter.

00:20:53.370 --> 00:20:58.620
Friends, family, the
love of your life,

00:20:58.620 --> 00:21:03.650
perhaps children, and
your own kind of success.

00:21:03.650 --> 00:21:08.380
And may you wander
but always come home.

00:21:08.380 --> 00:21:10.190
Best of luck to you all.

00:21:10.190 --> 00:21:11.150
Congratulations.

00:21:11.150 --> 00:21:14.114
[APPLAUSE]

00:21:41.340 --> 00:21:43.320
Thank you so much, Dean Pfister.

00:21:43.320 --> 00:21:45.950
And good afternoon,
class of 2014.

00:21:45.950 --> 00:21:49.260
My name is Michele Dimino,
and I am your class secretary.

00:21:49.260 --> 00:21:50.530
My name is Michelle Luo.

00:21:50.530 --> 00:21:54.280
I am one half of the senior
class tech and media team.

00:21:54.280 --> 00:21:57.540
And I'm Karen Xiao, the other
half of your tech and media

00:21:57.540 --> 00:21:59.830
team.

00:21:59.830 --> 00:22:03.430
It's hard to believe that four
years have passed since we sat

00:22:03.430 --> 00:22:07.250
in this very place at our
freshman convocation, strangers

00:22:07.250 --> 00:22:10.460
to one another and to
the campus around us.

00:22:10.460 --> 00:22:14.270
After hundreds of hours spent
in dining halls and classrooms

00:22:14.270 --> 00:22:17.350
and thousands of steps
through the gates of the yard,

00:22:17.350 --> 00:22:20.920
these places and faces
have become, at the least,

00:22:20.920 --> 00:22:22.330
familiar to us.

00:22:22.330 --> 00:22:25.560
And often, they've
come to mean much more.

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:28.090
Tomorrow when we
receive our diplomas

00:22:28.090 --> 00:22:31.170
and officially become
alumni of Harvard college,

00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:34.500
we will do so in houses
that have become our homes

00:22:34.500 --> 00:22:39.100
and with people who have
truly become our family here.

00:22:39.100 --> 00:22:41.350
It has been our pleasure
as your class committee

00:22:41.350 --> 00:22:45.580
to see our 2014 community grow
and strengthen during a very

00:22:45.580 --> 00:22:47.360
special senior year.

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:49.160
And it has been my
particular pleasure

00:22:49.160 --> 00:22:51.620
to flood your inboxes
with emails and event

00:22:51.620 --> 00:22:54.510
updates along the way.

00:22:54.510 --> 00:22:56.580
In the years to
come, we look forward

00:22:56.580 --> 00:22:59.610
to making this community
even more connected

00:22:59.610 --> 00:23:03.960
and to continuing to see old
classmates become new friends.

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:07.220
As you look ahead, know that
the Harvard alumni network will

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:10.960
be there for you, and that your
classmates will have your back

00:23:10.960 --> 00:23:13.650
and be at your side,
just as they are today

00:23:13.650 --> 00:23:17.140
and have been since we came to
Harvard as the class of 2014

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:18.010
four years ago.

00:23:20.690 --> 00:23:25.040
We know that for all of you
here, adventure is out there.

00:23:25.040 --> 00:23:26.560
Being spread out
across the world

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:27.880
doesn't mean that
our class will not

00:23:27.880 --> 00:23:29.671
be able to stay connected
with one another.

00:23:35.410 --> 00:23:39.040
We are overjoyed to see so
many of you pinned on Map14.

00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:40.720
From those of you
staying in Boston

00:23:40.720 --> 00:23:44.030
to those of you moving
halfway across the world,

00:23:44.030 --> 00:23:47.120
remember that wherever
you are, you can always

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:50.250
revisit the class of
2014 Facebook page

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:52.480
whenever you're feeling
nostalgic for senior bar

00:23:52.480 --> 00:23:54.260
photos.

00:23:54.260 --> 00:23:56.735
You can always reach out
to your city captains who

00:23:56.735 --> 00:23:59.540
will be dedicated to keeping
you in touch with each other

00:23:59.540 --> 00:24:02.620
as well as with
other Harvard alumni.

00:24:02.620 --> 00:24:05.040
Finding a new friend
in an old city

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:08.290
can be as simple as browsing
our city Facebook groups

00:24:08.290 --> 00:24:11.350
or opening up Map14.

00:24:11.350 --> 00:24:13.060
Even as we go our
separate ways, we

00:24:13.060 --> 00:24:17.340
will continue to learn and
grow together as a class.

00:24:17.340 --> 00:24:19.840
Today marks the end of
a four year journey,

00:24:19.840 --> 00:24:21.590
but the beginning
of lifelong one.

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:28.430
By Friday at 5:00 PM, we
will lose swipe access

00:24:28.430 --> 00:24:29.963
to all Harvard buildings.

00:24:29.963 --> 00:24:31.815
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:31.815 --> 00:24:36.075
And with that, we lose our
beloved daily dining service,

00:24:36.075 --> 00:24:39.150
the $65 of Board
Plus every semester,

00:24:39.150 --> 00:24:40.930
and the ability to
walk out the door

00:24:40.930 --> 00:24:44.430
and be surrounded by hundreds
of loving tutors, friends,

00:24:44.430 --> 00:24:46.560
and classmates.

00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:48.090
But we will never
lose the memories

00:24:48.090 --> 00:24:50.480
of all nighters spent
in the dining halls,

00:24:50.480 --> 00:24:54.220
the delicious taste of
Cape Cod chips from Fly-By,

00:24:54.220 --> 00:24:57.820
and the experiences we have
shared these past four years.

00:24:57.820 --> 00:25:00.660
Don't forget that those
friends and memories are just

00:25:00.660 --> 00:25:04.526
a Facebook post, a
text, or an email away.

00:25:04.526 --> 00:25:06.900
We hope to see you cheering
in the stands at Harvard Yale

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:09.950
next year, and returning
for our five year reunion,

00:25:09.950 --> 00:25:12.090
and many more after that.

00:25:12.090 --> 00:25:13.550
Don't be a stranger.

00:25:13.550 --> 00:25:16.176
Keep in touch.

00:25:16.176 --> 00:25:18.596
[APPLAUSE]

00:25:28.780 --> 00:25:31.270
Thank you, Michele,
Karen, and Michelle.

00:25:31.270 --> 00:25:32.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:33.850
We are looking
forward to staying

00:25:33.850 --> 00:25:36.340
connected in the coming years.

00:25:36.340 --> 00:25:39.660
I am Caitlin Fai, Currier
House representative.

00:25:39.660 --> 00:25:42.060
I am Sarah June, Lowell
House representative.

00:25:45.110 --> 00:25:48.070
During these past four
years, we had taken a part

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:50.530
in a number of
Harvard traditions.

00:25:50.530 --> 00:25:55.150
We played Yale in football
and won each November.

00:25:55.150 --> 00:25:58.240
We celebrated our houses
with shouts and cheers,

00:25:58.240 --> 00:26:01.450
on housing day and
every day since.

00:26:01.450 --> 00:26:03.820
Some of us even jumped
from Weeks Bridge

00:26:03.820 --> 00:26:06.785
into the questionable
waters of the Charles River.

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:14.210
Some of these traditions
were stayed and respectable,

00:26:14.210 --> 00:26:18.380
such as convocation, while
others were decidedly less

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:21.660
proper, such as primal scream.

00:26:21.660 --> 00:26:24.590
Running a naked lap around
Harvard Yard on the night

00:26:24.590 --> 00:26:27.730
before exam period may not
seem like a typical Harvard

00:26:27.730 --> 00:26:31.800
tradition, but we
participated undeterred.

00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:35.730
Through traditions we have been
able to cultivate and celebrate

00:26:35.730 --> 00:26:39.900
past, present, and future
shared experiences.

00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:43.730
Today we are here to introduce
one of the more respectable

00:26:43.730 --> 00:26:48.080
Harvard traditions, the
tradition of class color.

00:26:48.080 --> 00:26:52.550
The class color tradition began
when the senior class of 1882

00:26:52.550 --> 00:26:55.860
wore green and white rowing
uniforms to distinguish itself

00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:59.750
from the other class boats
on the Charles River.

00:26:59.750 --> 00:27:03.770
The three original colors--
green, orange, and blue--

00:27:03.770 --> 00:27:08.280
represented Harvard's fiercest
athletic and academic rivals--

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:10.830
Dartmouth, Princeton, and Yale.

00:27:10.830 --> 00:27:13.080
Wearing the colors of
our rivals was a way

00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:15.275
to express victory
over them, to triumph.

00:27:19.570 --> 00:27:23.310
In 1904, students began to wear
pins with their class colors

00:27:23.310 --> 00:27:24.730
on them.

00:27:24.730 --> 00:27:27.440
As the tradition developed,
wearing the colors

00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:31.590
on t-shirts and ties create a
sense of unity and cohesiveness

00:27:31.590 --> 00:27:33.660
among the class.

00:27:33.660 --> 00:27:37.620
The class color tradition
lapsed in the mid 20th century,

00:27:37.620 --> 00:27:41.230
but the senior class
revived it in 2012.

00:27:41.230 --> 00:27:45.200
Today we continue the
tradition as the class of 2014

00:27:45.200 --> 00:27:48.090
receives the color green.

00:27:48.090 --> 00:27:51.100
Green was originally meant
to represent Dartmouth,

00:27:51.100 --> 00:27:53.870
one of our foremost
athletic rivals.

00:27:53.870 --> 00:27:57.270
However, in the past year
Harvard swept Dartmouth

00:27:57.270 --> 00:28:02.430
in men and women's soccer,
basketball, squash, swimming,

00:28:02.430 --> 00:28:04.520
and even ice hockey.

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:06.670
Since it's not much
of a rivalry anymore,

00:28:06.670 --> 00:28:08.900
green signifies
something different

00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:11.700
for the Harvard class of 2014.

00:28:11.700 --> 00:28:15.150
It represents
growth and renewal.

00:28:15.150 --> 00:28:17.700
Since we arrived on
campus four years ago,

00:28:17.700 --> 00:28:20.260
we have changed and matured.

00:28:20.260 --> 00:28:22.675
Some of us would barely
recognize our freshman year

00:28:22.675 --> 00:28:25.450
selves, and all of
us have broadened

00:28:25.450 --> 00:28:28.070
our intellectual horizons.

00:28:28.070 --> 00:28:31.470
Now we are ready to move
forward from Harvard,

00:28:31.470 --> 00:28:35.356
wisened and enlightened,
or so we think.

00:28:35.356 --> 00:28:38.150
Yet our class color
green will be passed on

00:28:38.150 --> 00:28:42.800
to the rising sophomores,
class of 2017.

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:45.590
They will adopt it
as their own, and we,

00:28:45.590 --> 00:28:48.220
during this time of
rebirth, will move forward

00:28:48.220 --> 00:28:49.920
to new things.

00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:53.370
Class of 2014, we
will leave Harvard,

00:28:53.370 --> 00:28:55.310
but will forever be
linked through the color

00:28:55.310 --> 00:28:57.590
green to the
classes that follow.

00:28:57.590 --> 00:28:58.556
Thank you.

00:28:58.556 --> 00:29:01.036
[APPLAUSE]

00:29:06.988 --> 00:29:07.980
Go Roland!

00:29:07.980 --> 00:29:09.468
[CHEERING]

00:29:09.468 --> 00:29:12.610
Good afternoon, 2014.

00:29:12.610 --> 00:29:17.690
My name is Roland Yang, and I
am one of your class marshals.

00:29:17.690 --> 00:29:19.800
I have the honor
and the pleasure

00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:23.480
of introducing our incoming
president of the Harvard Alumni

00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:29.290
Association, Cynthia Torres,
Harvard College class of 1980,

00:29:29.290 --> 00:29:33.320
and Harvard Business
School class of 1984.

00:29:33.320 --> 00:29:36.230
Hailing from Santa
Monica, California,

00:29:36.230 --> 00:29:38.930
Torres was a resident
of Lowell House

00:29:38.930 --> 00:29:43.490
and a government concentrator
in her undergraduate years.

00:29:43.490 --> 00:29:46.930
She also served as a business
tutor in Winthrop House

00:29:46.930 --> 00:29:49.990
during her time at
the Business School.

00:29:49.990 --> 00:29:52.640
Torres has been active
in alumni affairs

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:56.590
ever since her graduation,
and her involvement

00:29:56.590 --> 00:30:00.850
reads like a guide on how to
stay connected with Harvard.

00:30:00.850 --> 00:30:04.760
From chairing two committees at
the Harvard Alumni Association

00:30:04.760 --> 00:30:07.610
to serving as first Vice
President of the Executive

00:30:07.610 --> 00:30:12.800
Committee, Torres has seen
many aspects of alumni life,

00:30:12.800 --> 00:30:15.190
and she brings a
wealth of experiences

00:30:15.190 --> 00:30:17.800
to the Harvard community.

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:22.690
Our speaker today has a
special bond with the year 2014

00:30:22.690 --> 00:30:24.590
and with our class.

00:30:24.590 --> 00:30:31.560
First, 2014 marks Torres' 30th
reunion at the Business School.

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:35.260
Second, Torres was with
us from the very beginning

00:30:35.260 --> 00:30:39.430
of our Harvard careers, serving
as a marshal at our freshman

00:30:39.430 --> 00:30:41.190
convocation.

00:30:41.190 --> 00:30:45.340
Third and most important,
she is the proud parent

00:30:45.340 --> 00:30:48.380
of Spencer Gisser, who
as a fellow senior,

00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:51.310
is graduating with us from
Pforzheimer House this year.

00:30:55.320 --> 00:30:57.810
We are delighted to have
Cynthia Torres with us

00:30:57.810 --> 00:31:00.140
on this incredibly
special occasion

00:31:00.140 --> 00:31:04.380
as she welcomes us to our new
Harvard community as alumni.

00:31:04.380 --> 00:31:06.970
Please join me in
welcoming Cynthia Torres,

00:31:06.970 --> 00:31:09.342
incoming president of the
Harvard Alumni Association.

00:31:09.342 --> 00:31:12.294
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:18.690 --> 00:31:22.720
Thank you Roland, for that
kind and generous introduction.

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:26.580
Greetings class of 2014.

00:31:26.580 --> 00:31:32.420
Today you are one of 1,650
graduating undergraduates.

00:31:32.420 --> 00:31:36.230
Tomorrow you'll be
welcomed by President Faust

00:31:36.230 --> 00:31:40.520
into the fellowship of
educated men and women

00:31:40.520 --> 00:31:43.220
and join a larger
global community

00:31:43.220 --> 00:31:48.640
of 320,000 proud Harvard alumni.

00:31:48.640 --> 00:31:52.700
As the incoming president of
the Harvard Alumni Association,

00:31:52.700 --> 00:31:58.870
I want to talk about what
the HAA can do for you.

00:31:58.870 --> 00:32:02.750
As Roland mentioned, I do feel
a special bond with your class.

00:32:02.750 --> 00:32:07.440
Four years ago I served as
the lead marshal for the Mower

00:32:07.440 --> 00:32:11.930
Dormitory Group when you
marched into this same theater

00:32:11.930 --> 00:32:15.600
at your freshman convocation.

00:32:15.600 --> 00:32:19.360
I have returned to
campus often since then.

00:32:19.360 --> 00:32:23.500
One of your classmates is
my own son, Spencer Gisser,

00:32:23.500 --> 00:32:28.270
who today is a graduating
senior Pforzheimer House.

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:31.850
I am so proud of him.

00:32:31.850 --> 00:32:36.450
And in that way, I know
how all your parents feel.

00:32:36.450 --> 00:32:40.350
Students, please make a point
today of hugging your parents

00:32:40.350 --> 00:32:44.890
and thanking your family
for all their support.

00:32:44.890 --> 00:32:47.660
And yes, Spencer, babe,
I am talking to you.

00:32:47.660 --> 00:32:51.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:51.610 --> 00:32:55.730
When I entered Harvard
in 1976 from my hometown

00:32:55.730 --> 00:32:59.550
of Eagle Rock in
urban Los Angeles,

00:32:59.550 --> 00:33:02.710
I had no idea what to expect.

00:33:02.710 --> 00:33:05.910
I had never lived in snow.

00:33:05.910 --> 00:33:10.070
I was mystified by the rivalry
between the fans of the Boston

00:33:10.070 --> 00:33:13.500
Red Sox and the
New York Yankees.

00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:19.530
I was a Dodgers fan being
from L.A. I didn't know anyone

00:33:19.530 --> 00:33:24.460
at Harvard and I wasn't sure how
I'd fit in or even if I would.

00:33:24.460 --> 00:33:27.060
My father had
grown up in poverty

00:33:27.060 --> 00:33:30.220
as a Mexican-American
migrant farm worker,

00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:32.790
and my mother was
a homemaker raising

00:33:32.790 --> 00:33:36.090
four children on a tight budget.

00:33:36.090 --> 00:33:40.910
And four years later
when I sat where you are,

00:33:40.910 --> 00:33:45.410
I imagined that my Harvard
experience, as transformative

00:33:45.410 --> 00:33:51.520
as it was, would
end upon graduation.

00:33:51.520 --> 00:33:55.470
But in fact it was
just the beginning.

00:33:55.470 --> 00:33:59.510
Since graduation I have
volunteered for Harvard

00:33:59.510 --> 00:34:02.830
every year in every city
that I have lived in,

00:34:02.830 --> 00:34:04.460
and I've moved a lot.

00:34:04.460 --> 00:34:07.000
Whenever I've moved
someplace new,

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.540
I would contact the
local Harvard Club

00:34:09.540 --> 00:34:12.070
and ask how I could help.

00:34:12.070 --> 00:34:15.179
My freshman concerns
of not knowing

00:34:15.179 --> 00:34:19.429
how I'd fit into a
community were gone forever.

00:34:19.429 --> 00:34:22.860
I have sat at many
registration tables,

00:34:22.860 --> 00:34:25.800
met the Harvard alumni
who came through the door,

00:34:25.800 --> 00:34:28.630
and listened to
captivating lectures

00:34:28.630 --> 00:34:31.120
by the Harvard faculty.

00:34:31.120 --> 00:34:34.500
I have also interviewed some
of the amazing high school

00:34:34.500 --> 00:34:38.150
students who apply for
admission each year.

00:34:38.150 --> 00:34:40.940
You can do these things too.

00:34:40.940 --> 00:34:48.300
My Harvard alumni mantra is
attend, volunteer, learn,

00:34:48.300 --> 00:34:50.580
and connect.

00:34:50.580 --> 00:34:55.440
This last year, I traveled
around the world with the HAA

00:34:55.440 --> 00:35:02.210
meeting alumni leaders in Sofia,
Bulgaria, in Santiago, Chile,

00:35:02.210 --> 00:35:05.140
and in Sydney, Australia.

00:35:05.140 --> 00:35:09.180
For me, the true
magic of Harvard

00:35:09.180 --> 00:35:16.540
is its people, its extraordinary
students, faculty, and alumni.

00:35:16.540 --> 00:35:17.720
Think about it.

00:35:17.720 --> 00:35:22.810
You're joining a club that
includes presidents, the Chief

00:35:22.810 --> 00:35:27.830
Justice of the Supreme Court,
Nobel Prize winners, Pulitzer

00:35:27.830 --> 00:35:32.990
Prize winners, Emmy Award
winners, technology titans,

00:35:32.990 --> 00:35:36.250
leaders of social movements.

00:35:36.250 --> 00:35:39.490
We even have Weezer's
Rivers Cuomo and Rashida

00:35:39.490 --> 00:35:42.090
Jones to make us all feel cool.

00:35:42.090 --> 00:35:43.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:46.820
The alumni community that
you are about to join

00:35:46.820 --> 00:35:49.410
is here for you.

00:35:49.410 --> 00:35:52.990
Networking is entirely
different from what

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:56.460
I thought it was when
I was in college.

00:35:56.460 --> 00:35:59.170
I have discovered that
the best networkers want

00:35:59.170 --> 00:36:03.080
to know what they
can do for you.

00:36:03.080 --> 00:36:05.770
So come to the HAA's
next global networking

00:36:05.770 --> 00:36:09.350
night, which is free of
charge and is happening

00:36:09.350 --> 00:36:14.710
in over 70 cities around
the world on June 23.

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:18.690
Another way to connect is to
join a Harvard shared interest

00:36:18.690 --> 00:36:19.860
group.

00:36:19.860 --> 00:36:24.490
These are virtual communities of
alumni that you access through

00:36:24.490 --> 00:36:32.980
our website, which is
alumni.harvard.edu/cigs.

00:36:32.980 --> 00:36:36.560
There are now nearly 50
shared interest groups

00:36:36.560 --> 00:36:40.510
with about 20,000
participating alumni.

00:36:40.510 --> 00:36:43.060
The groups include
Harvard Alumni

00:36:43.060 --> 00:36:48.120
In Wine and Food, the Harvard
Asian American Alumni Alliance,

00:36:48.120 --> 00:36:53.130
Harvard Alumni Entrepreneurs,
Harvard Radcliffe Science

00:36:53.130 --> 00:36:58.780
Fiction Networking
Society, and Harvardwood.

00:36:58.780 --> 00:37:00.960
All of Harvard's
shared interest groups

00:37:00.960 --> 00:37:06.770
are looking for young alumni and
welcome your energy and ideas.

00:37:06.770 --> 00:37:11.120
For the past three years I have
co-chaired an alumni careers

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:14.960
task force that works closely
with the Office of Career

00:37:14.960 --> 00:37:16.900
Services.

00:37:16.900 --> 00:37:21.690
Our group has developed a long
list of distinguished alumni

00:37:21.690 --> 00:37:25.830
that spans the entire
occupational spectrum.

00:37:25.830 --> 00:37:29.260
These alumni are
here to help you.

00:37:29.260 --> 00:37:31.770
The earliest years
of their own careers

00:37:31.770 --> 00:37:36.790
often involved false
starts and meandering.

00:37:36.790 --> 00:37:40.140
But we also know that who
the undergraduates really

00:37:40.140 --> 00:37:43.910
want to talk to are
the recent grads

00:37:43.910 --> 00:37:48.200
to ask, what is it
really like out there?

00:37:48.200 --> 00:37:50.980
So we hope that a
short time from now

00:37:50.980 --> 00:37:52.950
you will volunteer
through Crimson Compass

00:37:52.950 --> 00:37:56.540
to aid students in their
career explorations.

00:37:56.540 --> 00:37:58.730
The Harvard Alumni
Association will

00:37:58.730 --> 00:38:03.540
be conducting our annual
meeting here tomorrow afternoon.

00:38:03.540 --> 00:38:06.580
Please join us back here
after your house graduation

00:38:06.580 --> 00:38:09.110
ceremonies conclude.

00:38:09.110 --> 00:38:13.990
We want you to discover that
your Harvard experience turns

00:38:13.990 --> 00:38:20.160
out to be so much more than your
four years here in Cambridge.

00:38:20.160 --> 00:38:25.500
