a failure in that regard.

00:49:04.020 --> 00:49:09.090
And so today, I come
bearing a simple message.

00:49:09.090 --> 00:49:14.320
We have endured what we
perceive as a failure

00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:18.350
without really even
knowing what failure is.

00:49:18.350 --> 00:49:21.820
We have conflated
failure with not getting

00:49:21.820 --> 00:49:23.870
exactly what we want.

00:49:23.870 --> 00:49:29.360
And in doing so, have diminished
our many accomplishments.

00:49:29.360 --> 00:49:31.770
Take me for example.

00:49:31.770 --> 00:49:36.460
I am a first generation
college student on one side.

00:49:36.460 --> 00:49:38.400
I spent the majority
of my free time

00:49:38.400 --> 00:49:41.790
here acting for thousands of
people, making them laugh,

00:49:41.790 --> 00:49:45.010
and sometimes making them cry.

00:49:45.010 --> 00:49:49.250
I was even once kissed square
on the mouth by Jack Bauer,

00:49:49.250 --> 00:49:50.750
if you can believe it.

00:49:50.750 --> 00:49:51.280
I was.

00:49:53.790 --> 00:49:59.010
I also couldn't get
into a final club.

00:49:59.010 --> 00:50:03.850
I lost my bid to become Business
Manager of the Harvard Crimson.

00:50:03.850 --> 00:50:07.050
I sometimes struggle
with grades.

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:09.530
And I didn't secure a full
time job with the company

00:50:09.530 --> 00:50:12.090
that I interned with.

00:50:12.090 --> 00:50:16.790
To the untrained eye,
what does that look like?

00:50:16.790 --> 00:50:22.310
Success, or something different?

00:50:22.310 --> 00:50:23.770
Let me switch
gears for a moment.

00:50:23.770 --> 00:50:29.450
Harvard students,
we love to compare.

00:50:29.450 --> 00:50:32.540
After every exam
we clump together

00:50:32.540 --> 00:50:33.910
and we talk about what we wrote.

00:50:33.910 --> 00:50:36.420
I mean, who hasn't
done that before?

00:50:36.420 --> 00:50:41.300
We check our Facebooks and
see just how many people

00:50:41.300 --> 00:50:45.150
have more impressive jobs or
graduate opportunities than we

00:50:45.150 --> 00:50:46.830
do.

00:50:46.830 --> 00:50:50.290
Frankly, there's no more
blatant comparison of ourselves

00:50:50.290 --> 00:50:53.700
to others then there is on
Housing Day, and no more

00:50:53.700 --> 00:50:57.180
blatant perception of failure.

00:50:57.180 --> 00:50:58.490
I got quadded.

00:50:58.490 --> 00:51:01.300
I thought that was a failure.

00:51:01.300 --> 00:51:03.390
I did.

00:51:03.390 --> 00:51:10.720
I then got n minus 2 housing
within the quad, and I thought,

00:51:10.720 --> 00:51:14.440
that's a failure
within a failure.

00:51:14.440 --> 00:51:15.870
That's a fail-ception.

00:51:15.870 --> 00:51:18.017
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:18.017 --> 00:51:20.350
I think that Edgar Allan Poe
must have written something

00:51:20.350 --> 00:51:20.910
about that.

00:51:24.010 --> 00:51:25.010
Don't look that up.

00:51:25.010 --> 00:51:30.790
It's just strange for a group
of individuals hand picked

00:51:30.790 --> 00:51:34.410
by Harvard admissions to
bring continue successes

00:51:34.410 --> 00:51:38.380
to the greatest university
in the world, bar none,

00:51:38.380 --> 00:51:42.510
to at times feel compelled
to focus on looking

00:51:42.510 --> 00:51:45.910
for miniature failures
in the comparisons

00:51:45.910 --> 00:51:49.150
that we draw with one another.

00:51:49.150 --> 00:51:51.820
Why?

00:51:51.820 --> 00:51:54.390
I'm not saying that
comparing is bad.

00:51:54.390 --> 00:51:56.860
Sometimes comparison is great.

00:51:56.860 --> 00:51:59.290
The inherent sense of
competition among students

00:51:59.290 --> 00:52:03.350
here is extremely beneficial to
our development in some ways.

00:52:03.350 --> 00:52:08.030
It requires us to perform
better and to work harder.

00:52:08.030 --> 00:52:12.190
A little competition is
healthy and it makes you grow.

00:52:12.190 --> 00:52:14.510
But I am saying
that a lot of times

00:52:14.510 --> 00:52:20.250
we take these comparisons in
the most negative way possible.

00:52:20.250 --> 00:52:25.150
An aspiring doctor may feel
relatively unaccomplished

00:52:25.150 --> 00:52:29.840
when hearing about a friend's
cool tech internship.

00:52:29.840 --> 00:52:32.740
The lack of a thesis
paper from your suite

00:52:32.740 --> 00:52:35.270
of academic
accomplishments becomes

00:52:35.270 --> 00:52:38.960
a perceived intellectual
inferiority, despite your lack

00:52:38.960 --> 00:52:40.800
of interest in academic writing.

00:52:44.180 --> 00:52:50.260
Being ignored by or rejected
from a social organization

00:52:50.260 --> 00:52:52.860
becomes an assertion
that you may

00:52:52.860 --> 00:53:00.950
be cool or popular, but just
not enough for your peers.

00:53:00.950 --> 00:53:05.910
And from these differences that
we rebrand as deficiencies,

00:53:05.910 --> 00:53:10.680
we manufacture failure.

00:53:10.680 --> 00:53:13.600
But we're not failures, are we?

00:53:13.600 --> 00:53:14.340
No.

00:53:14.340 --> 00:53:15.750
Of course not.

00:53:15.750 --> 00:53:20.740
Without getting too cloyingly
preachy about Harvard,

00:53:20.740 --> 00:53:23.440
we are all on the
path to living out

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:25.250
remarkably successful lives.

00:53:25.250 --> 00:53:28.700
And we knew that from
the moment we got here.

00:53:28.700 --> 00:53:31.130
We opened that email
from admissions

00:53:31.130 --> 00:53:33.880
after smashing the Refresh
button again and again

00:53:33.880 --> 00:53:36.110
on our inbox.

00:53:36.110 --> 00:53:42.740
We saw our acceptance and
we said, well, I'm set.

00:53:42.740 --> 00:53:48.190
And in a lot of cases, it didn't
even take a year for some of us

00:53:48.190 --> 00:53:53.850
to see some great thing that one
of our peers did and say, whoa.

00:53:53.850 --> 00:53:57.420
I'm no longer set.

00:53:57.420 --> 00:53:59.950
Our futures become
uncertain to us,

00:53:59.950 --> 00:54:04.060
often based on something
totally out of our control.

00:54:04.060 --> 00:54:06.830
And what's more, we
don't take the time

00:54:06.830 --> 00:54:11.320
to truly celebrate the
success in the first place.

00:54:11.320 --> 00:54:13.900
It might appear
that way sometimes

00:54:13.900 --> 00:54:19.640
in the form of a celebratory
meal or drink or gift.

00:54:19.640 --> 00:54:24.060
But at a certain point,
albeit a relatively minor one,

00:54:24.060 --> 00:54:28.430
it becomes an issue
of you being behind

00:54:28.430 --> 00:54:31.870
and you needing to catch
up so that you are not

00:54:31.870 --> 00:54:35.200
considered a failure.

00:54:35.200 --> 00:54:37.670
Now I don't mean to make
Harvard students out

00:54:37.670 --> 00:54:43.000
to be petulant frenemies who
constantly feel pessimistic

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:44.540
about their abilities.

00:54:44.540 --> 00:54:46.010
They're not.

00:54:46.010 --> 00:54:51.420
They're diverse, down to
earth, and downright brilliant.

00:54:51.420 --> 00:54:55.080
Check out that fancy
literary device.

00:54:55.080 --> 00:54:57.320
And I'm honored to be
counted among the company

00:54:57.320 --> 00:55:00.020
of such talented individuals.

00:55:00.020 --> 00:55:06.800
But I am saying that sometimes,
not being first or the best

00:55:06.800 --> 00:55:10.230
can sour what we've
accomplished and drive us

00:55:10.230 --> 00:55:17.350
to saying or thinking, at
some point, I have failed.

00:55:17.350 --> 00:55:23.630
And as I said before, we
are so not failures at all.

00:55:23.630 --> 00:55:25.500
Look at us.

00:55:25.500 --> 00:55:31.740
We are poets,
musicians, artists.

00:55:31.740 --> 00:55:35.460
We are athletes and
champions at that.

00:55:35.460 --> 00:55:40.240
We are scientists, bound to
unlock the greatest discoveries

00:55:40.240 --> 00:55:43.020
heretofore in human history.

00:55:43.020 --> 00:55:45.450
We are future
politicians who will

00:55:45.450 --> 00:55:47.950
shape this nation
for the better.

00:55:47.950 --> 00:55:52.690
There may even be a future
president sitting in this crowd

00:55:52.690 --> 00:55:54.830
this afternoon.

00:55:54.830 --> 00:55:56.750
And guess what?

00:55:56.750 --> 00:56:03.960
That president might
not have had a 4.0.

00:56:03.960 --> 00:56:08.410
And that president may not
have gotten the dream job

00:56:08.410 --> 00:56:11.350
that he or she
thought they wanted.

00:56:11.350 --> 00:56:14.000
And you know what
I'm willing to bet?

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:20.136
That president is sitting here
today and listening to me talk

00:56:20.136 --> 00:56:23.450
and looking back on
his or her for years,

00:56:23.450 --> 00:56:29.580
and might be reminded of
the failures rather than

00:56:29.580 --> 00:56:34.010
the future, disregarding all
of the great things happening

00:56:34.010 --> 00:56:37.671
right now and those that
will happen in the many years

00:56:37.671 --> 00:56:38.170
to come.

00:56:40.840 --> 00:56:46.770
So I stand up here before
you and I look back

00:56:46.770 --> 00:56:51.240
at the 45 months since I first
stepped into Harvard Yard-- I

00:56:51.240 --> 00:56:56.230
know, it's a lot of months--
as a fresh-faced, fledgling

00:56:56.230 --> 00:56:56.730
freshman.

00:57:00.480 --> 00:57:02.880
And what do I see?

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:09.620
Well, I didn't get the social
standing I thought I wanted

00:57:09.620 --> 00:57:14.100
or the big leadership position
that I thought I wanted,

00:57:14.100 --> 00:57:18.090
or the grades that
I maybe wanted.

00:57:18.090 --> 00:57:21.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:21.150 --> 00:57:25.310
Or the job that I thought
I definitely wanted.

00:57:25.310 --> 00:57:30.050
On paper, that looks
a lot like failure.

00:57:30.050 --> 00:57:34.780
That's academic life,
personal life, social life,

00:57:34.780 --> 00:57:37.240
future professional life.

00:57:37.240 --> 00:57:42.398
On paper that's a
whole lot of nothing.

00:57:42.398 --> 00:57:45.450
You know what?

00:57:45.450 --> 00:57:48.130
That's fine.

00:57:48.130 --> 00:57:52.460
Because I didn't
really fail, did I?

00:57:52.460 --> 00:57:56.580
I just didn't get what
I thought I wanted.

00:57:56.580 --> 00:58:02.780
Instead, I got friendships
that will last a lifetime.

00:58:02.780 --> 00:58:07.930
I got a great job that I
love, keeps me close to home.

00:58:07.930 --> 00:58:11.100
I found a girl that I love.

00:58:11.100 --> 00:58:14.530
And I got a fantastic education.

00:58:14.530 --> 00:58:19.920
But I didn't get exactly
what I thought I wanted.

00:58:19.920 --> 00:58:23.301
None of us has always
gotten exactly what we want.

00:58:23.301 --> 00:58:26.270
And at one point or
another, we have all

00:58:26.270 --> 00:58:28.900
considered that failure.

00:58:28.900 --> 00:58:33.210
And it takes a long time to
resolve that perceived failure

00:58:33.210 --> 00:58:37.110
as a learning experience or as
an opportunity for other doors

00:58:37.110 --> 00:58:39.320
to open.

00:58:39.320 --> 00:58:42.800
But especially this
week, a week spent

00:58:42.800 --> 00:58:47.080
celebrating our hard
work and our triumphs,

00:58:47.080 --> 00:58:51.110
a week culminating in
a commencement so named

00:58:51.110 --> 00:58:54.220
because it marks
a new beginning,

00:58:54.220 --> 00:58:59.220
we should start
focusing on the success.

00:58:59.220 --> 00:59:03.660
Because in the end, we can try
to measure our relative level

00:59:03.660 --> 00:59:09.470
of success here at Harvard based
on the setbacks and the defeats

00:59:09.470 --> 00:59:11.818
and the B minuses.

00:59:11.818 --> 00:59:17.760
Or we can take a step back
and see just how little

00:59:17.760 --> 00:59:21.440
that matters in the long run.

00:59:21.440 --> 00:59:27.250
Only then will we truly
recognize how far we've come

00:59:27.250 --> 00:59:28.300
and how far we'll go.

00:59:31.300 --> 00:59:34.275
I failed Harvard.

00:59:37.330 --> 00:59:40.100
Or did I?

00:59:40.100 --> 00:59:40.979
Thank you.

00:59:40.979 --> 00:59:42.935
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:56.140 --> 01:00:00.140
Good afternoon, class of
2014, friends, and family.

01:00:00.140 --> 01:00:02.150
My name is Yolanda
Borquaye and I

01:00:02.150 --> 01:00:06.280
am one of the 2014
senior class marshals.

01:00:06.280 --> 01:00:08.660
Today I have the distinct
privilege and honor

01:00:08.660 --> 01:00:11.240
of introducing to you
a Pforzheimer House

01:00:11.240 --> 01:00:14.390
native and friend,
Christie DiSilvestro.

01:00:14.390 --> 01:00:16.722
Christie hails from
Haverford, Pennsylvania,

01:00:16.722 --> 01:00:18.180
and has spent much
of her time here

01:00:18.180 --> 01:00:21.570
at Harvard exploring the
intersection between psychology

01:00:21.570 --> 01:00:24.170
and medicine, particularly
as it pertains

01:00:24.170 --> 01:00:27.570
to the psychological issues
children and families face

01:00:27.570 --> 01:00:32.040
after traumatic injury
or long-term diagnosis.

01:00:32.040 --> 01:00:34.220
After graduation she'll
be continuing this passion

01:00:34.220 --> 01:00:37.165
in graduate school at the
University of Pennsylvania.

01:00:37.165 --> 01:00:39.540
When I asked several of her
friends to describe Christie,

01:00:39.540 --> 01:00:40.998
the two words that
they kept saying

01:00:40.998 --> 01:00:44.160
were kind and thoughtful,
and I am so honored

01:00:44.160 --> 01:00:47.380
and pleased that she'll be
addressing us here today.

01:00:47.380 --> 01:00:49.220
So without further
ado, please join me

01:00:49.220 --> 01:00:51.270
in welcoming our
next 2014 Harvard

01:00:51.270 --> 01:00:53.628
orator, Christie DiSilvestro.

01:00:53.628 --> 01:00:56.118
[APPLAUSE]

01:01:04.590 --> 01:01:10.270
A picture, a permanent record
of happiness or triumph or love,

01:01:10.270 --> 01:01:13.060
a small token to ensure
that a moment doesn't get

01:01:13.060 --> 01:01:15.140
lost in the fray.

01:01:15.140 --> 01:01:17.750
Photographs are everywhere.

01:01:17.750 --> 01:01:20.700
With the rise of Instagram
and the ever-growing Twitter

01:01:20.700 --> 01:01:23.570
and Facebook perfectly
coinciding with our college

01:01:23.570 --> 01:01:26.520
career, we have
endless opportunities

01:01:26.520 --> 01:01:30.380
to capture moments and
freeze them forever.

01:01:30.380 --> 01:01:33.730
We take pictures of
almost everything.

01:01:33.730 --> 01:01:36.790
We do this so much that we
don't think twice about it,

01:01:36.790 --> 01:01:39.310
and might not even realize
the significance of what

01:01:39.310 --> 01:01:41.040
we're capturing.

01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:43.390
Years from now we
will have the ability

01:01:43.390 --> 01:01:47.460
to look back on our college days
and have an array of memories

01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:51.670
to focus on, never having
to lose a flash of happiness

01:01:51.670 --> 01:01:55.440
as we grow more
distant from Harvard.

01:01:55.440 --> 01:01:59.230
But what about the memories
that we don't capture on film?

01:01:59.230 --> 01:02:02.730
The times when unexpected
challenges stop us

01:02:02.730 --> 01:02:04.840
in our tracks?

01:02:04.840 --> 01:02:07.800
These are the moments
when snapping a selfie

01:02:07.800 --> 01:02:11.110
is the furthest
thought from our minds.

01:02:11.110 --> 01:02:13.800
Think of all the tough
times that you've faced

01:02:13.800 --> 01:02:16.060
or the obstacles you've
helped a friend overcome,

01:02:16.060 --> 01:02:19.190
and how that's affected
you as a person.

01:02:19.190 --> 01:02:21.040
Think about surprising
opportunities

01:02:21.040 --> 01:02:22.905
that came your
way and caused you

01:02:22.905 --> 01:02:26.590
to choose a different path
than you had predicted.

01:02:26.590 --> 01:02:30.790
The truth is when we experience
something that changes us

01:02:30.790 --> 01:02:34.370
forever, whether
it is good or bad,

01:02:34.370 --> 01:02:37.540
we don't use an
iPhone to save it.

01:02:37.540 --> 01:02:39.670
We remember these
moments forever

01:02:39.670 --> 01:02:42.030
without the help of a lens.

01:02:42.030 --> 01:02:44.170
They can't be
captured in a picture.

01:02:44.170 --> 01:02:46.890
No words can easily
describe them.

01:02:46.890 --> 01:02:51.250
And yet, they define
our self-portrait.

01:02:51.250 --> 01:02:53.610
When we first
arrived on campus we

01:02:53.610 --> 01:02:56.530
were filled with the frenzy and
excitement of early freshman

01:02:56.530 --> 01:02:57.710
year.

01:02:57.710 --> 01:03:01.480
We had the opportunity to
entirely reinvent ourselves,

01:03:01.480 --> 01:03:03.840
starting fresh in a
place where no one had

01:03:03.840 --> 01:03:05.780
prior impressions of us.

01:03:05.780 --> 01:03:09.750
It was an adventurous, turn on
the camera type of experience

01:03:09.750 --> 01:03:12.960
when we pictured the story
of our new lives and the path

01:03:12.960 --> 01:03:16.800
that we would travel on
for the next four years.

01:03:16.800 --> 01:03:19.530
Now imagine that you could
read a letter written

01:03:19.530 --> 01:03:24.080
by that wide-eyed freshman
year self about who you were

01:03:24.080 --> 01:03:26.800
and what you wanted to become.

01:03:26.800 --> 01:03:29.490
What would be your
reaction today?

01:03:29.490 --> 01:03:31.630
Would those hopes
and beliefs map

01:03:31.630 --> 01:03:35.160
onto who you have
become as an individual?

01:03:35.160 --> 01:03:38.020
For all of us, our
college experience

01:03:38.020 --> 01:03:41.120
and even our identities
did not unfold

01:03:41.120 --> 01:03:44.070
in exactly the way we imagined.

01:03:44.070 --> 01:03:47.570
We have since migrated from
that first mold that we made.

01:03:47.570 --> 01:03:49.380
But the changes
we've experienced

01:03:49.380 --> 01:03:53.430
have made us into stronger,
more mature, and more resilient

01:03:53.430 --> 01:03:55.520
individuals.

01:03:55.520 --> 01:03:57.300
The event that has
changed the most

01:03:57.300 --> 01:03:59.710
crashed down on me in the
spring of my freshman year

01:03:59.710 --> 01:04:02.036
as a varsity water polo player.

01:04:02.036 --> 01:04:04.560
A double hip injury
assaulted my body

01:04:04.560 --> 01:04:07.920
and left me unable
to walk within days.

01:04:07.920 --> 01:04:11.100
The injury resulted in
two expensive surgeries

01:04:11.100 --> 01:04:13.690
and over six months on crutches.

01:04:13.690 --> 01:04:17.750
For more than two years, I
could not sit, stand, or walk

01:04:17.750 --> 01:04:19.400
liberally.

01:04:19.400 --> 01:04:21.730
Not only could I
not play sports,

01:04:21.730 --> 01:04:25.380
I couldn't navigate
campus, go to class,

01:04:25.380 --> 01:04:28.380
or live the normal life
of a college student.

01:04:28.380 --> 01:04:30.895
I took one semester of
final exams lying down

01:04:30.895 --> 01:04:34.820
in a bed in UHS and
another semester of finals

01:04:34.820 --> 01:04:37.170
standing and writing at a
podium while the proctor

01:04:37.170 --> 01:04:40.390
sat at the desks
because I could not sit.

01:04:40.390 --> 01:04:43.000
I was constantly in pain.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:46.310
But as our challenges often
do, this time of darkness

01:04:46.310 --> 01:04:50.660
showed me light and laughter
in places I never expected.

01:04:50.660 --> 01:04:53.410
An endearing new
nickname-- Crutchy--

01:04:53.410 --> 01:04:57.290
that I heard more often than
my real name, and a pair

01:04:57.290 --> 01:04:59.640
of crutches that I
covered in zebra tape

01:04:59.640 --> 01:05:04.280
helped give me a boost when
moving at a snail's pace.

01:05:04.280 --> 01:05:07.680
I received help from
people I had never met,

01:05:07.680 --> 01:05:11.220
from people whose names
I would never know.

01:05:11.220 --> 01:05:13.670
Harvard is notorious
for its selective hand

01:05:13.670 --> 01:05:17.000
picking of students, and
through my experience,

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:20.890
I learned that this campus is
full of the most compassionate

01:05:20.890 --> 01:05:22.270
people.

01:05:22.270 --> 01:05:25.200
I never felt alone in
such a warm community

01:05:25.200 --> 01:05:29.270
and received a helping hand
from everyone around me.

01:05:29.270 --> 01:05:32.800
In return, the most I could
do was lend my crutches

01:05:32.800 --> 01:05:35.560
to friends at parties
to help them meet guys,

01:05:35.560 --> 01:05:39.595
a tactics we found
surprisingly successful.

01:05:39.595 --> 01:05:42.390
[LAUGHTER]

01:05:42.390 --> 01:05:46.060
Tiny moments morphed
into great memories.

01:05:46.060 --> 01:05:48.640
Picture a handsome guy you
have a crush on inviting you

01:05:48.640 --> 01:05:50.910
to a party that you declined
because you can't walk up

01:05:50.910 --> 01:05:55.220
the stairs, so he offers
to give you a piggyback.

01:05:55.220 --> 01:05:59.620
I had to rely on others for
almost everything that I did.

01:05:59.620 --> 01:06:02.950
Even your classic Sunday
morning walk of shame

01:06:02.950 --> 01:06:05.590
was no longer independent.

01:06:05.590 --> 01:06:08.300
It's an entirely
different experience

01:06:08.300 --> 01:06:11.060
when he has to carry
you back to your dorm

01:06:11.060 --> 01:06:16.010
while his roommate carries
your crutches alongside him.

01:06:16.010 --> 01:06:20.010
If you're thinking that would
be awkward and hilarious,

01:06:20.010 --> 01:06:22.070
it totally was.

01:06:22.070 --> 01:06:26.100
But these memories are now
my most endearing treasures

01:06:26.100 --> 01:06:30.494
that sparked the beginning of
a long lasting relationship.

01:06:30.494 --> 01:06:34.070
When I look back at the
journey of my injury,

01:06:34.070 --> 01:06:35.840
my goals and my
impression of how

01:06:35.840 --> 01:06:40.210
I might fit into this
community completely changed.

01:06:40.210 --> 01:06:44.100
I tried to hold onto water polo
for two years after I was hurt,

01:06:44.100 --> 01:06:47.380
but I eventually
had to let that go.

01:06:47.380 --> 01:06:50.710
I learned to immerse
myself in joy.

01:06:50.710 --> 01:06:53.610
I learned how important
it is to surround yourself

01:06:53.610 --> 01:06:56.320
with the people who lift
you up-- in my case,

01:06:56.320 --> 01:06:59.290
sometimes literally--
and walk away

01:06:59.290 --> 01:07:01.950
from the ones who
bring you down.

01:07:01.950 --> 01:07:04.430
My injury was not a time
I was ready to pull out

01:07:04.430 --> 01:07:06.430
the camera and document.

01:07:06.430 --> 01:07:10.610
But it was important
and life changing.

01:07:10.610 --> 01:07:14.190
Many of our greatest lessons
are not learned in class

01:07:14.190 --> 01:07:16.220
or read in a textbook.

01:07:16.220 --> 01:07:19.640
We all tackled a huge
transition from the safety net

01:07:19.640 --> 01:07:21.520
of living at home
with our families

01:07:21.520 --> 01:07:24.140
to the autonomy of
a college campus.

01:07:24.140 --> 01:07:26.490
When we faced struggles,
we were forced

01:07:26.490 --> 01:07:29.050
to rely on our
friends and peers.

01:07:29.050 --> 01:07:32.780
We became mentors and shoulders
to lean on for others.

01:07:32.780 --> 01:07:35.810
Their hard times
became our challenges

01:07:35.810 --> 01:07:39.880
just as their moments of
joy became our celebrations.

01:07:39.880 --> 01:07:42.530
We created a new
definition of family,

01:07:42.530 --> 01:07:45.800
one that included all
those who are alongside us

01:07:45.800 --> 01:07:48.430
for our hurdles and heartaches.

01:07:48.430 --> 01:07:50.300
Through this
process, we developed

01:07:50.300 --> 01:07:52.650
our own unique
identities, preparing

01:07:52.650 --> 01:07:56.270
us to take on the real world.

01:07:56.270 --> 01:08:00.070
No matter what has caused you to
change over the past few years,

01:08:00.070 --> 01:08:04.570
embrace those changes and who
you have become as a result.

01:08:04.570 --> 01:08:06.690
Maybe you took an
elective senior year

01:08:06.690 --> 01:08:10.180
and surprised yourself with how
much you enjoyed the material,

01:08:10.180 --> 01:08:14.160
making you rethink your
career path late in the game.

01:08:14.160 --> 01:08:16.960
Maybe you had issues with
roommates and adjusting

01:08:16.960 --> 01:08:21.040
to a new living situation at
the beginning of a school year.

01:08:21.040 --> 01:08:23.620
Perhaps you made
a mistake, caused

01:08:23.620 --> 01:08:27.910
harm that you took the steps
to remedy and make right.

01:08:27.910 --> 01:08:30.290
Maybe you received
inspiring advice

01:08:30.290 --> 01:08:32.680
that made you turn your
life around and walk

01:08:32.680 --> 01:08:34.960
with more confidence.

01:08:34.960 --> 01:08:36.850
When you think of
the big moments that

01:08:36.850 --> 01:08:39.640
have affected your
college career,

01:08:39.640 --> 01:08:44.569
you don't need a digital
photograph to remember them.

01:08:44.569 --> 01:08:47.300
One of them, the
Boston Marathon,

01:08:47.300 --> 01:08:50.970
affected and unified
us unlike any other.

01:08:50.970 --> 01:08:53.750
Everyone remembers where
they were junior year when

01:08:53.750 --> 01:08:55.870
they heard about
the detonations,

01:08:55.870 --> 01:08:58.590
even if they weren't at
the marathon experiencing

01:08:58.590 --> 01:09:01.740
the terrifying panic firsthand.

01:09:01.740 --> 01:09:03.410
Everyone remembers
the entire day

01:09:03.410 --> 01:09:08.490
of lockdown later that week,
and the relief when it was over.

01:09:08.490 --> 01:09:11.479
This disaster taught
us the importance

01:09:11.479 --> 01:09:13.979
of appreciating the
strangers around us,

01:09:13.979 --> 01:09:16.090
knowing that at any
given moment they

01:09:16.090 --> 01:09:18.880
could be the very
ones to save us.

01:09:18.880 --> 01:09:22.399
It taught us to run to help
others rather than running

01:09:22.399 --> 01:09:23.859
away.

01:09:23.859 --> 01:09:26.490
As a class, leaning
on each other,

01:09:26.490 --> 01:09:31.180
we grew from this tragedy and
became stronger because of it.

01:09:31.180 --> 01:09:33.420
Eventually we
learned that it's OK

01:09:33.420 --> 01:09:35.569
if something blindsides
us and causes

01:09:35.569 --> 01:09:39.500
us to stray from the plan we
thought we were executing.

01:09:39.500 --> 01:09:41.124
Sometimes these
blindsides can teach

01:09:41.124 --> 01:09:43.800
us to appreciate what is
around us even more than we

01:09:43.800 --> 01:09:45.470
did before.

01:09:45.470 --> 01:09:47.540
I personally have a
renewed appreciation

01:09:47.540 --> 01:09:50.180
for the little things
that surround me.

01:09:50.180 --> 01:09:52.720
I now appreciate the
ability to walk freely

01:09:52.720 --> 01:09:55.710
around campus, the
ability to concentrate

01:09:55.710 --> 01:09:59.110
without the constant
reminder of physical pain,

01:09:59.110 --> 01:10:01.270
the ability to see
someone struggling

01:10:01.270 --> 01:10:03.160
and be able to offer
him or her that

01:10:03.160 --> 01:10:07.880
helping hand instead
of only receiving it.

01:10:07.880 --> 01:10:10.010
All these major changes
we have experienced

01:10:10.010 --> 01:10:15.590
in college-- the good and the
bad times that shape us-- these

01:10:15.590 --> 01:10:18.800
are the images that
captured memories,

01:10:18.800 --> 01:10:21.750
that aren't in a Facebook
album, but instead

01:10:21.750 --> 01:10:26.020
compile and create the album
of us, the self-portrait

01:10:26.020 --> 01:10:29.760
with moments we will
always hold dear.

01:10:29.760 --> 01:10:32.050
Embrace the changes
that come your way

01:10:32.050 --> 01:10:35.200
and enrich your
development as a person.

01:10:35.200 --> 01:10:37.940
Enjoy the little
things, for one day,

01:10:37.940 --> 01:10:42.240
you may look back and realize
they were the big things.

01:10:42.240 --> 01:10:46.250
So enjoy all the laughs
that make life so wonderful,

01:10:46.250 --> 01:10:50.230
but also take time to stop and
think about all the moments

01:10:50.230 --> 01:10:54.460
and changes that actually got
you to where you are today.

01:10:54.460 --> 01:10:58.800
The people you've leaned on and
those who have leaned on you,

01:10:58.800 --> 01:11:03.210
the friends you've celebrated
with in triumph and progress,

01:11:03.210 --> 01:11:06.912
the unexpected side roads
that you've traveled on.

01:11:06.912 --> 01:11:08.716
And then, yes.

01:11:08.716 --> 01:11:10.420
Take a picture.

01:11:10.420 --> 01:11:13.740
But be sure to appreciate
the entire self-portrait

01:11:13.740 --> 01:11:15.850
you are truly capturing.

01:11:15.850 --> 01:11:18.540
And when something
memorable comes your way,

01:11:18.540 --> 01:11:24.706
don't never hesitate to say,
but first, let me take a selfie.

01:11:24.706 --> 01:11:26.182
[LAUGHTER]

01:11:26.182 --> 01:11:27.166
Thank you!

01:11:27.166 --> 01:11:29.626
[APPLAUSE]

01:11:40.450 --> 01:11:48.170
Good afternoon faculty, friends,
family, and the class of 2014.

01:11:48.170 --> 01:11:50.115
My name is Catherine
Philbin, and I

01:11:50.115 --> 01:11:52.980
am thrilled to be serving
as the representative

01:11:52.980 --> 01:11:55.115
from the great Dunster House.

01:11:55.115 --> 01:11:58.050
[CHEERS]

01:11:58.050 --> 01:12:01.960
Today it is my honor to
introduce the Richard Glover

01:12:01.960 --> 01:12:06.190
and Henry Russell
Ames Memorial Award.

01:12:06.190 --> 01:12:11.030
As many of you already know,
the members of the class of 2014

01:12:11.030 --> 01:12:16.140
have shown a great commitment
to the service of others.

01:12:16.140 --> 01:12:21.050
This includes the service
to Harvard, the nation,

01:12:21.050 --> 01:12:23.850
and our global community.

01:12:23.850 --> 01:12:27.210
Many members of our great
class have gone four years

01:12:27.210 --> 01:12:31.580
without any recognition for
their hard work, compassion,

01:12:31.580 --> 01:12:34.550
and determination
to help others.

01:12:34.550 --> 01:12:37.740
However, the Ames
Award works to honor

01:12:37.740 --> 01:12:42.100
two unsung heroes of our class.

01:12:42.100 --> 01:12:48.720
On June 19, 1935, Richard Glover
Ames and Henry Russell Ames,

01:12:48.720 --> 01:12:52.410
brothers and Harvard
students, gave their lives

01:12:52.410 --> 01:12:56.200
to save their father who was
washed overboard during a storm

01:12:56.200 --> 01:12:59.000
off the coast of Newfoundland.

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:01.190
Every year since,
the Ames Award has

01:13:01.190 --> 01:13:03.940
been given in their
memory to recognize

01:13:03.940 --> 01:13:07.120
two members of our class
who have shown energy

01:13:07.120 --> 01:13:09.270
in helping others
and who exhibit

01:13:09.270 --> 01:13:12.560
the same heroic
character and inspiring

01:13:12.560 --> 01:13:15.620
leadership as the Ames brothers.

01:13:15.620 --> 01:13:19.070
The selection committee received
a large number of nominations

01:13:19.070 --> 01:13:24.420
from faculty, house masters,
tutors, and fellow seniors,

01:13:24.420 --> 01:13:27.610
and the decision process
was incredibly difficult,

01:13:27.610 --> 01:13:31.410
and we could not be more
proud of our classmates who

01:13:31.410 --> 01:13:36.290
have made such a tremendous
impact on their communities.

01:13:36.290 --> 01:13:39.820
I invite all of the nominees
for this year's Ames Award

01:13:39.820 --> 01:13:42.370
to please stand
and be recognized.

01:13:42.370 --> 01:13:44.835
[APPLAUSE]

01:14:00.130 --> 01:14:03.030
At this time, it is my
pleasure to introduce

01:14:03.030 --> 01:14:05.580
Akshay Sharma,
class marshal, who

01:14:05.580 --> 01:14:09.720
will present the first
recipient of the Ames Award.

01:14:09.720 --> 01:14:14.530
[APPLAUSE]

01:14:14.530 --> 01:14:15.720
Thank you, Cath.

01:14:15.720 --> 01:14:17.030
Good afternoon.

01:14:17.030 --> 01:14:18.020
What a beautiful day.

01:14:18.020 --> 01:14:19.665
[LAUGHTER]

01:14:22.400 --> 01:14:25.680
Congratulations again
to all the nominees,

01:14:25.680 --> 01:14:28.880
and thank you for your
outstanding leadership

01:14:28.880 --> 01:14:32.910
and heroism in
service to others.

01:14:32.910 --> 01:14:35.740
The Ames Award is
presented annually

01:14:35.740 --> 01:14:39.230
as the senior class leaves
the gates of Harvard,

01:14:39.230 --> 01:14:45.040
and it reminds us the importance
of connecting, engaging,

01:14:45.040 --> 01:14:50.680
and serving in the communities
that we are about to enter.

01:14:50.680 --> 01:14:54.030
Each one of us
has within ourself

01:14:54.030 --> 01:14:58.450
the potential to affect
positive change in this world

01:14:58.450 --> 01:15:01.692
when we combine the
skills we have developed,

01:15:01.692 --> 01:15:05.650
the passions that we
have cultivated here

01:15:05.650 --> 01:15:07.980
with an awareness of
the existing need.

01:15:10.850 --> 01:15:15.220
Ultimately, the success
that we measure in our lives

01:15:15.220 --> 01:15:22.880
will not be defined by how high
we reach or how far we travel,

01:15:22.880 --> 01:15:25.690
but by how many lives we change.

01:15:29.410 --> 01:15:32.280
Our first of today's
Ames Award recipients

01:15:32.280 --> 01:15:36.706
has been dedicated in his
pursuit to help those in need.

01:15:36.706 --> 01:15:40.350
In the face of grave
financial adversity,

01:15:40.350 --> 01:15:44.490
his sheer passion for learning
and high scholastic achievement

01:15:44.490 --> 01:15:47.280
afforded him the
opportunity to receive

01:15:47.280 --> 01:15:50.920
a fully funded
primary education.

01:15:50.920 --> 01:15:54.540
Upon arriving at
Harvard, he has set

01:15:54.540 --> 01:15:58.470
to the task of giving
back to the community that

01:15:58.470 --> 01:16:02.480
supported him in the past.

01:16:02.480 --> 01:16:05.220
Originally from
Swaziland, a country

01:16:05.220 --> 01:16:07.530
with one of the
highest incidence

01:16:07.530 --> 01:16:11.400
rates of HIV infection
in the world,

01:16:11.400 --> 01:16:14.260
he has dedicated
his last four years

01:16:14.260 --> 01:16:17.420
to combating the disease
that claimed many

01:16:17.420 --> 01:16:20.902
in his community, both
friends and family.

01:16:24.030 --> 01:16:27.660
He has spent the last three
years at the Reagan Institute

01:16:27.660 --> 01:16:32.320
of MIT, Harvard, and the
Massachusetts General Hospital

01:16:32.320 --> 01:16:36.920
researching the
immunological basis of HIV.

01:16:36.920 --> 01:16:40.110
He spent summers at the
Don McKenzie Hospital

01:16:40.110 --> 01:16:43.850
in Durban, South Africa,
implementing testing,

01:16:43.850 --> 01:16:51.280
counseling, and treatment
adherence programs for HIV.

01:16:51.280 --> 01:16:54.290
And last year, he
founded an organization

01:16:54.290 --> 01:16:57.130
by the name of
[? Salbona ?] Health,

01:16:57.130 --> 01:17:01.140
tasked with increasing and
improving the health of HIV

01:17:01.140 --> 01:17:05.100
patients globally by
increasing patient adherence

01:17:05.100 --> 01:17:10.360
to integral
antiretroviral therapies.

01:17:10.360 --> 01:17:12.530
Next year he will be
back in his home country

01:17:12.530 --> 01:17:15.960
Swaziland, working to
combat and find solutions

01:17:15.960 --> 01:17:21.330
to structural problems linked
to poor HIV treatment adherence,

01:17:21.330 --> 01:17:24.800
mainly food security.

01:17:24.800 --> 01:17:28.520
Members of this recipient's
house community at Harvard

01:17:28.520 --> 01:17:31.460
are confident that
he will succeed

01:17:31.460 --> 01:17:34.640
in bringing about a
genuine transformation

01:17:34.640 --> 01:17:36.810
in his community.

01:17:36.810 --> 01:17:40.840
They cite the nobility
and genuineness

01:17:40.840 --> 01:17:44.730
of his passion for
public service.

01:17:44.730 --> 01:17:48.420
And all the while, his
extraordinary achievement

01:17:48.420 --> 01:17:53.230
is coupled with
genuine humility.

01:17:53.230 --> 01:17:58.550
Please join me in congratulating
our first Ames Award recipient,

01:17:58.550 --> 01:18:02.840
resident of Pforzheimer House,
fellow member of the class

01:18:02.840 --> 01:18:09.690
of 2014, a healer of
the world, and hero,

01:18:09.690 --> 01:18:11.436
[? Mjhanke ?] [? Shbangu. ?]

01:18:11.436 --> 01:18:13.916
[APPLAUSE]

01:19:06.040 --> 01:19:10.560
It is now my honor to introduce
Erin Drake, class marshal who

01:19:10.560 --> 01:19:13.565
will present the second
recipient of the Ames award.

01:19:13.565 --> 01:19:14.941
[CHEERS]

01:19:14.941 --> 01:19:16.384
Go Erin!

01:19:16.384 --> 01:19:17.830
Woo!

01:19:17.830 --> 01:19:19.910
Thank you Cath, and
congratulations again,

01:19:19.910 --> 01:19:23.700
[? Mjhanke. ?]
Hello, class of 2014.

01:19:23.700 --> 01:19:26.591
You all look very
warm out there.

01:19:26.591 --> 01:19:27.340
It's warm up here.

01:19:27.340 --> 01:19:29.560
OK.

01:19:29.560 --> 01:19:33.330
Our next Richard Glover Ames
and Henry Russell Ames Award

01:19:33.330 --> 01:19:36.860
goes to a woman whose
recommender described her

01:19:36.860 --> 01:19:43.240
as a force of nature, an
advocate, a mentor, and someone

01:19:43.240 --> 01:19:47.180
who is relentlessly
loyal, keeping her friends

01:19:47.180 --> 01:19:51.270
a top priority, even when school
and extracurriculars could

01:19:51.270 --> 01:19:53.330
easily distract.

01:19:53.330 --> 01:19:56.340
This woman is someone
who I and many of you

01:19:56.340 --> 01:19:58.590
have met over the
past four years.

01:19:58.590 --> 01:20:02.410
She was a participant in the
First Year Urban program,

01:20:02.410 --> 01:20:06.950
a peer counselor for Room
13, and a tireless volunteer,

01:20:06.950 --> 01:20:10.720
supervisor, and director at
the Phillips Brooks House

01:20:10.720 --> 01:20:13.940
association's Harvard
Square Homeless Shelter.

01:20:13.940 --> 01:20:15.900
Alternatively,
you could know her

01:20:15.900 --> 01:20:20.130
as a girl who had a
Facebook picture with Drake.

01:20:20.130 --> 01:20:23.790
During her time here she
has studied psychology,

01:20:23.790 --> 01:20:27.270
but has learned to be a selfless
leader and someone whose

01:20:27.270 --> 01:20:31.010
friends describe as more
dependable than anyone,

01:20:31.010 --> 01:20:34.210
compassionate, and empathetic.

01:20:34.210 --> 01:20:37.770
Now she leads a team of
students in their effort

01:20:37.770 --> 01:20:41.250
to establish the first entirely
student run youth homeless

01:20:41.250 --> 01:20:43.920
shelter in the nation.

01:20:43.920 --> 01:20:47.720
Regardless of when or how
you came in contact with her,

01:20:47.720 --> 01:20:51.420
I'm sure she didn't just list
off her activities, leadership

01:20:51.420 --> 01:20:55.160
roles, and famous
friends as I just did.

01:20:55.160 --> 01:20:59.080
I'm sure that because,
like most unsung heroes,

01:20:59.080 --> 01:21:02.920
she lets her work
speak for itself.

01:21:02.920 --> 01:21:07.170
Well today, on a day when
there's time and an opportunity

01:21:07.170 --> 01:21:11.400
to honor two of many
unsung heroes in our class,

01:21:11.400 --> 01:21:18.830
join me in congratulating the
next 2014 Richard Glover Ames

01:21:18.830 --> 01:21:23.660
and Henry Russell Ames Award
recipient, Sarah Rosenkrantz.

01:21:23.660 --> 01:21:25.990
[APPLAUSE]

01:22:01.630 --> 01:22:06.790
Congratulations to the
2014 Ames recipients.

01:22:06.790 --> 01:22:09.240
[APPLAUSE]

