Good afternoon, everyone.

01:22:18.795 --> 01:22:21.170
My name is Raina Gandhi, and
I'm the proud representative

01:22:21.170 --> 01:22:23.086
of Mather House on the
senior class committee.

01:22:23.086 --> 01:22:25.770
[CHEERS]

01:22:25.770 --> 01:22:27.640
I'm Basil Williams,
and I'm proud to be

01:22:27.640 --> 01:22:29.380
the representative
of Pforzheimer House.

01:22:32.060 --> 01:22:34.800
Looking back to when we
last sat in this yard,

01:22:34.800 --> 01:22:37.630
during our freshman
convocation, we

01:22:37.630 --> 01:22:40.110
had high hopes for
the next four years.

01:22:40.110 --> 01:22:42.070
We expected that
we would change,

01:22:42.070 --> 01:22:45.110
that we would grow and
develop into smarter and more

01:22:45.110 --> 01:22:49.540
thoughtful scholars,
citizens, and people.

01:22:49.540 --> 01:22:53.860
Yet what we didn't
necessarily think about then

01:22:53.860 --> 01:22:58.040
was how growth depends not
only on positive change,

01:22:58.040 --> 01:23:00.780
but also on loss.

01:23:00.780 --> 01:23:04.470
Each loss develops
our character,

01:23:04.470 --> 01:23:07.670
teaches us something
new about life,

01:23:07.670 --> 01:23:11.213
and may challenge or
reinforce our own beliefs.

01:23:14.370 --> 01:23:16.800
The most tragic losses
involve the passing

01:23:16.800 --> 01:23:18.320
of those who we love.

01:23:18.320 --> 01:23:23.020
Many of us have lost relatives,
family, friends, and classmates

01:23:23.020 --> 01:23:26.940
without whom we would not
have reached this occasion.

01:23:26.940 --> 01:23:29.410
There are classmates who
started with us at Harvard

01:23:29.410 --> 01:23:32.670
but will not be walking with
us at commencement tomorrow.

01:23:32.670 --> 01:23:35.610
These classes have shaped
our experiences here

01:23:35.610 --> 01:23:38.950
and deserve to be recognized
for their contribution

01:23:38.950 --> 01:23:41.670
as long with ours.

01:23:41.670 --> 01:23:43.760
Please join us in
a moment of silence

01:23:43.760 --> 01:23:47.720
to remember the family, friends,
and members of the university

01:23:47.720 --> 01:23:50.260
community who are
not amongst us today.

01:24:05.000 --> 01:24:07.800
Thank you.

01:24:07.800 --> 01:24:11.460
As we graduate
tomorrow we wonder,

01:24:11.460 --> 01:24:14.010
where do we go from here?

01:24:14.010 --> 01:24:16.790
We'll be facing new
challenges after we

01:24:16.790 --> 01:24:19.410
pass through these gates.

01:24:19.410 --> 01:24:23.160
Yet we don't have
to face them alone.

01:24:23.160 --> 01:24:27.790
Cody Laramie wrote,
"We are part of lives

01:24:27.790 --> 01:24:32.450
we have yet to live and see."

01:24:32.450 --> 01:24:35.630
The lives we are a part
of are not just our own,

01:24:35.630 --> 01:24:39.020
but those of our
loved ones as well.

01:24:39.020 --> 01:24:42.490
Reach out to those around
you for support and guidance.

01:24:42.490 --> 01:24:45.980
Hold onto the memories
and relationships

01:24:45.980 --> 01:24:49.710
we've built during
our time here.

01:24:49.710 --> 01:24:52.690
They can help carry us
through both challenging times

01:24:52.690 --> 01:24:58.240
and triumphant times, trying
times, and joyous times.

01:24:58.240 --> 01:24:59.760
Thank you.

01:24:59.760 --> 01:25:02.260
[APPLAUSE]

01:25:10.760 --> 01:25:14.760
Good afternoon seniors,
friends, family, and loved ones

01:25:14.760 --> 01:25:16.880
joining us here today.

01:25:16.880 --> 01:25:18.990
Thank you to Raina and
Basil for their touching

01:25:18.990 --> 01:25:21.560
and beautiful remarks.

01:25:21.560 --> 01:25:25.390
My name is Anthony Palillo and I
am one of the 2014 senior class

01:25:25.390 --> 01:25:28.190
marshals.

01:25:28.190 --> 01:25:31.720
I am honored and excited to be
introducing Quincy House native

01:25:31.720 --> 01:25:36.870
and a good friend, Jenna Martin,
as our 2014 Female Ivy Orator.

01:25:36.870 --> 01:25:39.866
Jenna is originally from
Los Angeles, California.

01:25:39.866 --> 01:25:43.370
At Harvard, Jenna was an English
concentrator, the head writer

01:25:43.370 --> 01:25:46.630
of On Harvard Time, an on
campus comedic news show,

01:25:46.630 --> 01:25:49.390
and a member of the
Lampoon Lit Staff.

01:25:49.390 --> 01:25:52.560
Jenna was also involved with
sketch comedy on campus,

01:25:52.560 --> 01:25:55.800
and during her summers she
interned at The Daily Show

01:25:55.800 --> 01:25:58.190
with Jon Stewart
and The New Yorker,

01:25:58.190 --> 01:26:01.550
where she was published twice
on the magazine's website.

01:26:01.550 --> 01:26:04.890
After graduation, she will
be returning to Los Angeles

01:26:04.890 --> 01:26:08.640
to pursue a career as
a television writer.

01:26:08.640 --> 01:26:10.610
Without further
ado, please join me

01:26:10.610 --> 01:26:13.420
in welcoming the amazing,
extremely talented,

01:26:13.420 --> 01:26:16.954
and wonderful Jenna Martin,
our 2014 Female Ivy Orator.

01:26:16.954 --> 01:26:19.439
[APPLAUSE]

01:26:25.410 --> 01:26:26.300
Thank you, Anthony.

01:26:29.820 --> 01:26:33.180
I'd like to thank you all for
coming, family and friends

01:26:33.180 --> 01:26:36.480
especially, because,
let's face it.

01:26:36.480 --> 01:26:38.146
No one likes going
to graduations.

01:26:41.350 --> 01:26:46.290
With apologies to any recent
middle school graduates,

01:26:46.290 --> 01:26:49.870
kindergarten graduation
is the last cute one.

01:26:49.870 --> 01:26:53.240
[LAUGHTER]

01:26:53.240 --> 01:26:55.480
And coming to this
one is like going

01:26:55.480 --> 01:27:01.870
to a wedding for 1,655
couples when you really

01:27:01.870 --> 01:27:03.800
only care about one--

01:27:03.800 --> 01:27:05.260
[LAUGHTER

01:27:05.260 --> 01:27:06.160
--if that.

01:27:06.160 --> 01:27:10.780
[LAUGHTER]

01:27:10.780 --> 01:27:14.270
To the esteemed
professors and TFs,

01:27:14.270 --> 01:27:17.200
you've been to so
many graduations

01:27:17.200 --> 01:27:21.120
that I sincerely hope
you're playing a drinking

01:27:21.120 --> 01:27:22.625
game to get through this one.

01:27:22.625 --> 01:27:25.560
[LAUGHTER]

01:27:25.560 --> 01:27:28.585
I'll even say some key
words to get you chugging.

01:27:31.220 --> 01:27:32.240
Harvard.

01:27:32.240 --> 01:27:34.096
[LAUGHTER]

01:27:36.880 --> 01:27:38.040
Graduation.

01:27:38.040 --> 01:27:40.200
[LAUGHTER]

01:27:40.200 --> 01:27:41.170
Future.

01:27:41.170 --> 01:27:42.948
[LAUGHTER]

01:27:42.948 --> 01:27:43.447
Compassion.

01:27:46.360 --> 01:27:50.390
To the class of 2014,
I imagine we're all

01:27:50.390 --> 01:27:54.520
feeling some mix of
anxiety and relief.

01:27:54.520 --> 01:27:58.440
And if you're anything like
me, a little bit of anxiety

01:27:58.440 --> 01:28:03.630
is enough to overwhelm
whatever else you're feeling.

01:28:03.630 --> 01:28:07.380
That anxiety can make
you prematurely nostalgic

01:28:07.380 --> 01:28:11.680
for the days when your biggest
problem was a five to seven

01:28:11.680 --> 01:28:17.470
page paper, also known as a four
page paper with wide margins

01:28:17.470 --> 01:28:19.270
and a really long title.

01:28:19.270 --> 01:28:21.234
[LAUGHTER]

01:28:24.180 --> 01:28:26.120
Or when your biggest
problem with that

01:28:26.120 --> 01:28:29.870
you have too many advisers.

01:28:29.870 --> 01:28:33.880
By now each of us has
had a freshman adviser,

01:28:33.880 --> 01:28:38.870
a peer advising fellow, a
proctor, a resident dean

01:28:38.870 --> 01:28:42.220
of freshman-- those
last two are different,

01:28:42.220 --> 01:28:47.850
by the way-- a sophomore
adviser, an Allston Burr

01:28:47.850 --> 01:28:52.330
resident dean, a sophomore
advising coordinator,

01:28:52.330 --> 01:28:57.221
a concentration adviser, and
for the masochistic, a thesis

01:28:57.221 --> 01:28:57.720
adviser.

01:28:57.720 --> 01:29:01.270
[LAUGHTER]

01:29:01.270 --> 01:29:05.602
I sincerely thank
all of my advisors.

01:29:05.602 --> 01:29:07.720
But I just want to
put it out there

01:29:07.720 --> 01:29:12.530
that Luke Skywalker defeated the
empire with only one advisor.

01:29:12.530 --> 01:29:14.515
[LAUGHTER]

01:29:18.710 --> 01:29:22.186
And he spoke in
incoherent aphorisms--

01:29:22.186 --> 01:29:25.890
[LAUGHTER]

01:29:25.890 --> 01:29:31.080
--had crazily
inconvenient office hours,

01:29:31.080 --> 01:29:34.900
and never once offered
Luke a mini Mr. Goodbar.

01:29:34.900 --> 01:29:37.320
[LAUGHTER]

01:29:37.320 --> 01:29:41.420
Despite the luxury
of too many advisers,

01:29:41.420 --> 01:29:43.420
there are some
questions on our minds

01:29:43.420 --> 01:29:47.010
right now that no one
can answer for certain.

01:29:47.010 --> 01:29:50.730
Like, will the clubs I
joined be enough to convince

01:29:50.730 --> 01:29:56.420
my future children
that I used to be cool?

01:29:56.420 --> 01:30:01.900
Will my concentration have any
application in the real world?

01:30:01.900 --> 01:30:04.250
It's common at this
point to bring up

01:30:04.250 --> 01:30:06.090
folklore and mythology.

01:30:06.090 --> 01:30:09.450
[LAUGHTER]

01:30:09.450 --> 01:30:13.515
But I don't think Celtic studies
gets the attention it deserves.

01:30:13.515 --> 01:30:15.670
[LAUGHTER]

01:30:20.670 --> 01:30:23.010
Most people either
don't know what

01:30:23.010 --> 01:30:25.735
that is, or think you're
pronouncing it wrong.

01:30:25.735 --> 01:30:29.240
[LAUGHTER]

01:30:29.240 --> 01:30:33.270
And perhaps the scariest
question of all,

01:30:33.270 --> 01:30:37.010
did I peak in college?

01:30:37.010 --> 01:30:39.840
I think that there
are two and only

01:30:39.840 --> 01:30:43.120
two answers to this question.

01:30:43.120 --> 01:30:46.202
Absolutely not and,
you know, probably.

01:30:49.530 --> 01:30:53.980
I'll entertain the you
know, probably answer first.

01:30:53.980 --> 01:30:58.250
We're about to enter a scary
world where our dumb mistakes

01:30:58.250 --> 01:31:01.390
will be met with a dubious
look and a wisecrack

01:31:01.390 --> 01:31:04.140
about where we went to college.

01:31:04.140 --> 01:31:07.370
At least here if someone
says, ugh, there's

01:31:07.370 --> 01:31:11.920
no way you go to Harvard,
it's usually a pickup line.

01:31:11.920 --> 01:31:13.848
[LAUGHTER]

01:31:24.460 --> 01:31:28.840
If I may speak from my own fears
of having peaked in college,

01:31:28.840 --> 01:31:31.330
when I first came to
Harvard, a part of me

01:31:31.330 --> 01:31:34.920
just wanted to study
English and write comedy,

01:31:34.920 --> 01:31:38.320
but another part of me wanted
to discover something new that

01:31:38.320 --> 01:31:43.950
would become my passion, like
anthropology or conceptual art,

01:31:43.950 --> 01:31:45.770
but hopefully
investment banking.

01:31:45.770 --> 01:31:48.076
[LAUGHTER]

01:31:52.300 --> 01:31:55.380
Four years later, I'm
getting a degree in English,

01:31:55.380 --> 01:31:59.670
and every club I joined was
somehow related to comedy,

01:31:59.670 --> 01:32:02.350
with the arguable
exception of the Lampoon.

01:32:02.350 --> 01:32:04.795
[LAUGHTER]

01:32:10.670 --> 01:32:14.230
It turns out I can't be changed.

01:32:14.230 --> 01:32:18.665
If I may sum up my experience
in the metaphor-- oh, I'm sorry,

01:32:18.665 --> 01:32:20.380
a simile--

01:32:20.380 --> 01:32:23.530
[LAUGHTER]

01:32:23.530 --> 01:32:25.320
Who says an English
degree is useless?

01:32:28.180 --> 01:32:34.010
I'm like one of television's
many illustrious bad boys.

01:32:34.010 --> 01:32:40.820
Don Draper, Tony
Soprano, Chuck Bass.

01:32:40.820 --> 01:32:44.600
Harvard's Gen Ed requirements
and activity fairs

01:32:44.600 --> 01:32:48.390
are like another character
who thinks it can change me,

01:32:48.390 --> 01:32:51.370
but sorry Harvard.

01:32:51.370 --> 01:32:52.770
I can't be changed.

01:32:55.700 --> 01:32:58.470
And that's why this
day makes me sad.

01:32:58.470 --> 01:33:03.580
Because not only can I no longer
compare myself to Don Draper,

01:33:03.580 --> 01:33:05.430
but I also don't
know for certain

01:33:05.430 --> 01:33:10.380
if I'll find another place where
I can be so completely myself

01:33:10.380 --> 01:33:13.750
and still have friends
and feel fulfilled.

01:33:13.750 --> 01:33:16.880
Where else will I be
surrounded by so many people

01:33:16.880 --> 01:33:21.640
just being their dorky selves
and doing what they love?

01:33:21.640 --> 01:33:24.016
Except at a white collar prison.

01:33:24.016 --> 01:33:25.914
[LAUGHTER]

01:33:32.390 --> 01:33:36.440
So maybe it's all
downhill from here.

01:33:36.440 --> 01:33:39.150
Just like it's been downhill
for commencement day

01:33:39.150 --> 01:33:41.630
speakers since Oprah
came last year.

01:33:41.630 --> 01:33:43.554
[LAUGHTER]

01:33:49.340 --> 01:33:52.150
But I mean, seriously.

01:33:52.150 --> 01:33:56.700
Good luck tomorrow, former mayor
of something what's his face?

01:33:56.700 --> 01:33:58.656
[LAUGHTER]

01:34:04.530 --> 01:34:09.110
However, the one thing I do
like about graduation also

01:34:09.110 --> 01:34:13.560
leads me to believe that we
didn't all peak in college.

01:34:13.560 --> 01:34:16.490
My fellow graduates,
there's probably

01:34:16.490 --> 01:34:20.360
someone in the class of
2014 who makes you think,

01:34:20.360 --> 01:34:22.020
well, I'm screwed.

01:34:22.020 --> 01:34:26.440
But that guy is
going to be amazing.

01:34:26.440 --> 01:34:30.330
Well, graduation allows
you to share something

01:34:30.330 --> 01:34:32.270
with that person.

01:34:32.270 --> 01:34:34.120
And I'll bet
there's someone else

01:34:34.120 --> 01:34:37.180
who feels the same
way about you.

01:34:37.180 --> 01:34:40.050
Why, the person
who looks up to you

01:34:40.050 --> 01:34:45.840
could even be speaking right
now if your name is Zamyla Chan.

01:34:45.840 --> 01:34:49.970
[CHEERS]

01:34:49.970 --> 01:34:53.870
If you're still worried that you
might have peaked in college,

01:34:53.870 --> 01:34:56.640
then think of your
favorite Harvard grad.

01:34:56.640 --> 01:35:00.440
Could be JFK, could
be Natalie Portman.

01:35:00.440 --> 01:35:03.326
Mine hands down is John Adams.

01:35:07.340 --> 01:35:09.580
I mean, his life
probably didn't turn out

01:35:09.580 --> 01:35:12.890
the way he expected
when he graduated,

01:35:12.890 --> 01:35:17.430
but he still became
our second president.

01:35:17.430 --> 01:35:21.957
You might even say he was
the Yale of presidents.

01:35:21.957 --> 01:35:23.945
[LAUGHTER]

01:35:27.430 --> 01:35:33.080
He married an incredible lady
and inspired an entire mini

01:35:33.080 --> 01:35:34.070
series.

01:35:34.070 --> 01:35:36.415
[LAUGHTER]

01:35:40.640 --> 01:35:42.930
When I was accepted
into Harvard,

01:35:42.930 --> 01:35:47.270
I couldn't wait to go to the
same school as our grouchiest

01:35:47.270 --> 01:35:50.080
founding father.

01:35:50.080 --> 01:35:53.770
You might even say I
came for the John Adams

01:35:53.770 --> 01:35:56.300
and then stayed
for the Sam Adams.

01:35:56.300 --> 01:35:59.910
[LAUGHTER]

01:35:59.910 --> 01:36:01.420
Yeah, but please don't say that.

01:36:01.420 --> 01:36:04.920
My parents are in the audience.

01:36:04.920 --> 01:36:09.010
My point is, the person who
made you excited to come here

01:36:09.010 --> 01:36:12.710
should also make you
excited to leave.

01:36:12.710 --> 01:36:18.470
Class of 2014, I'm not
saying you can do anything.

01:36:18.470 --> 01:36:21.240
As you will discover
tomorrow, you

01:36:21.240 --> 01:36:23.969
can't look good
in a cap and gown.

01:36:23.969 --> 01:36:27.140
[LAUGHTER]

01:36:27.140 --> 01:36:29.310
But at least there's
a good chance

01:36:29.310 --> 01:36:32.000
you didn't peak in college.

01:36:32.000 --> 01:36:35.840
Congratulations to the class
of 2014 and their families.

01:36:35.840 --> 01:36:38.300
[APPLAUSE]

01:36:47.995 --> 01:36:51.230
Thank you, Jenna, for
a beautiful oration.

01:36:51.230 --> 01:36:56.440
Good afternoon class of
2014, friends, and family.

01:36:56.440 --> 01:37:00.230
My name is Natalia Duarte, and
I am the senior class committee

01:37:00.230 --> 01:37:02.065
representative for
Leverett House.

01:37:02.065 --> 01:37:03.780
[CHEERS]

01:37:03.780 --> 01:37:04.480
Yay, bunnies!

01:37:04.480 --> 01:37:05.960
[LAUGHS]

01:37:05.960 --> 01:37:09.010
The person I am now
introducing actually

01:37:09.010 --> 01:37:13.210
once had the task of introducing
me at a Leverett House charity

01:37:13.210 --> 01:37:14.900
date auction.

01:37:14.900 --> 01:37:19.450
When I thought I was going to
be going for the lowest bid

01:37:19.450 --> 01:37:24.120
he turned the tables, riled up
the crowd with southern twang

01:37:24.120 --> 01:37:27.740
and innuendos,
and somehow had me

01:37:27.740 --> 01:37:32.420
auctioned as one of the most
expensive prizes of the night.

01:37:32.420 --> 01:37:35.440
He made me feel like
the belle of the ball,

01:37:35.440 --> 01:37:38.470
and now I must do the same.

01:37:38.470 --> 01:37:41.220
Today I have the
distinct privilege

01:37:41.220 --> 01:37:46.000
of introducing someone who
is not only a fellow Leverett

01:37:46.000 --> 01:37:47.370
House resident.

01:37:47.370 --> 01:37:51.530
He's a very dear friend to
me, and has been over my time

01:37:51.530 --> 01:37:53.270
at Harvard.

01:37:53.270 --> 01:37:57.480
Zack Guzman is one of
those rare individuals

01:37:57.480 --> 01:38:01.690
who always somehow
manages to make your day,

01:38:01.690 --> 01:38:04.970
and with whom there is
never a dull moment.

01:38:04.970 --> 01:38:08.020
Originally from Virginia,
Zack has anchored

01:38:08.020 --> 01:38:11.840
Harvard sketch comedy
show On Harvard Time

01:38:11.840 --> 01:38:17.620
and broadcasted sports for WHRB,
Harvard Student radio station,

01:38:17.620 --> 01:38:21.210
including a recent stint
in Spokane, Washington,

01:38:21.210 --> 01:38:24.710
covering Harvard's
March Madness victory.

01:38:24.710 --> 01:38:26.740
This experience
got him a full five

01:38:26.740 --> 01:38:29.990
seconds of fame on television.

01:38:29.990 --> 01:38:34.010
Zack would like to thank his
roommates, Andrew Walsh, Joe

01:38:34.010 --> 01:38:39.610
Lair, Matt Lowe, and James Sun
for always being there for him.

01:38:39.610 --> 01:38:42.770
And even though this
isn't a date auction,

01:38:42.770 --> 01:38:45.600
Zack would like to remind
the ladies of the crowd

01:38:45.600 --> 01:38:48.320
that love knows no age.

01:38:48.320 --> 01:38:51.130
Getting a little
desperate, aren't we?

01:38:51.130 --> 01:38:54.170
Ladies and gentlemen,
without further ado,

01:38:54.170 --> 01:38:59.100
I present to you Zack Guzman,
your 2014 Male Ivy Orator.

01:38:59.100 --> 01:39:01.485
[APPLAUSE]

01:39:08.499 --> 01:39:09.290
Thank you, Natalia.

01:39:11.800 --> 01:39:16.110
Hello fellow classmates,
family, and encroached

01:39:16.110 --> 01:39:17.480
upon squirrels of the yard.

01:39:20.420 --> 01:39:25.010
My name is Zack Guzman,
and I am in love.

01:39:25.010 --> 01:39:27.530
I have been in an
ongoing relationship

01:39:27.530 --> 01:39:30.500
for quite some time,
and perhaps some of you

01:39:30.500 --> 01:39:33.340
out in the audience, or
dare I say sitting up here

01:39:33.340 --> 01:39:39.610
with me on stage, might think
that this is a foolish notion.

01:39:39.610 --> 01:39:42.000
But I am not alone.

01:39:42.000 --> 01:39:45.640
I wouldn't be surprised if every
one of us in the class of 2014

01:39:45.640 --> 01:39:48.900
said the same thing.

01:39:48.900 --> 01:39:52.220
You see, our love
affair started even

01:39:52.220 --> 01:39:55.240
before we met the
love of our lives.

01:39:55.240 --> 01:39:57.020
In high school we
were desperately

01:39:57.020 --> 01:39:59.090
searching for a
significant other,

01:39:59.090 --> 01:40:00.810
and we set our eyes
on the most sought

01:40:00.810 --> 01:40:06.710
after, desirable piece of
assuredness on the market.

01:40:06.710 --> 01:40:09.150
She had everything my
hormone-filled teen self could

01:40:09.150 --> 01:40:10.950
ask for.

01:40:10.950 --> 01:40:14.410
Intellect, financial
stability, and as we

01:40:14.410 --> 01:40:19.120
saw with the whole satanic black
mask thing, a reverse tiger

01:40:19.120 --> 01:40:21.480
mom and Drew Faust who
allowed Harvard the freedom

01:40:21.480 --> 01:40:23.420
to do whatever she
wanted in the basement.

01:40:23.420 --> 01:40:25.400
[LAUGHTER]

01:40:28.870 --> 01:40:31.880
But as we learned at
the first chance dance,

01:40:31.880 --> 01:40:33.800
you can't just walk
up and tell someone

01:40:33.800 --> 01:40:36.800
you want to spend the rest
of your life with him or her.

01:40:36.800 --> 01:40:38.470
No, no.

01:40:38.470 --> 01:40:41.940
As society dictates, the
more appropriate strategy

01:40:41.940 --> 01:40:43.766
is to tell this to their friend.

01:40:43.766 --> 01:40:46.200
[LAUGHTER]

01:40:46.200 --> 01:40:49.210
To instill the appropriate
level of jealousy,

01:40:49.210 --> 01:40:52.810
I reached out to Stanford,
Harvard's tanner Californian

01:40:52.810 --> 01:40:53.310
friend.

01:40:53.310 --> 01:40:55.820
[LAUGHTER]

01:40:55.820 --> 01:41:01.090
But I missed the chitchat of
startups, golf, and something

01:41:01.090 --> 01:41:04.820
about the weather being
an unbearable 64 degrees.

01:41:04.820 --> 01:41:07.350
I decided to cut things off.

01:41:07.350 --> 01:41:10.870
It would be better for her
this way, and in the end,

01:41:10.870 --> 01:41:14.000
we caught Harvard's eye.

01:41:14.000 --> 01:41:16.220
The true problem,
though, was how many

01:41:16.220 --> 01:41:19.250
others saw what we
saw in our love.

01:41:19.250 --> 01:41:23.250
On our Tinder profile which,
for the parents in the crowd,

01:41:23.250 --> 01:41:26.280
is today's premier and
shadiest iPhone dating app--

01:41:26.280 --> 01:41:28.870
[LAUGHTER]

01:41:28.870 --> 01:41:32.220
--Harvard had 35,023
people swipe her

01:41:32.220 --> 01:41:35.635
to the right, which you only do
with the most attractive users.

01:41:39.510 --> 01:41:42.160
To put that in perspective--
because some of you

01:41:42.160 --> 01:41:45.230
might not know this--
in my four years here,

01:41:45.230 --> 01:41:49.100
my farmers only profile, which
is described as Tinder for,

01:41:49.100 --> 01:41:54.820
quote, "Good old country folk,"
has been viewed only once

01:41:54.820 --> 01:41:56.754
by a farmer in rural
Mass with the username

01:41:56.754 --> 01:41:58.420
XOXOHarvardSexyFunGuy
[? #FeanDister. ?]

01:42:02.812 --> 01:42:05.277
[LAUGHTER]

01:42:12.690 --> 01:42:15.470
Serious love prospects
only, Dean Pfister.

01:42:19.380 --> 01:42:22.490
But lo and behold, we
were swiped to the right

01:42:22.490 --> 01:42:25.590
too, sparking the
honeymoon phase, where

01:42:25.590 --> 01:42:28.740
nothing at all about the
other person could bother you.

01:42:28.740 --> 01:42:30.970
Not her coldness, not
her crippling fear

01:42:30.970 --> 01:42:33.640
to only refer to herself as a
school in Boston when others

01:42:33.640 --> 01:42:36.540
ask, and not the kinky
demands that everyone pee

01:42:36.540 --> 01:42:38.572
on John Harvard's foot
in order to graduate.

01:42:41.380 --> 01:42:43.750
We found it cute that
security guards wanted

01:42:43.750 --> 01:42:45.990
to check and make sure
we weren't stealing books

01:42:45.990 --> 01:42:48.100
from the library.

01:42:48.100 --> 01:42:51.130
You didn't mind the
fact that Harvard's idea

01:42:51.130 --> 01:42:55.810
of culinary variety meant
variously colored yet strangely

01:42:55.810 --> 01:42:58.980
similarly tasting
sauces on top of freshly

01:42:58.980 --> 01:43:04.172
cut, cage free endangered fish
known simply as [? Sui ?].

01:43:04.172 --> 01:43:07.010
[LAUGHTER]

01:43:07.010 --> 01:43:11.090
And if it wasn't beef
fettuccine Alfredo night--

01:43:11.090 --> 01:43:12.855
which God help us
all if it was--

01:43:12.855 --> 01:43:14.580
[LAUGHTER]

01:43:14.580 --> 01:43:17.400
--you didn't mind Harvard
bought the recycled fiberglass

01:43:17.400 --> 01:43:20.030
version of single
ply toilet paper

01:43:20.030 --> 01:43:22.510
and limited your use
to two roles per week.

01:43:22.510 --> 01:43:25.210
[LAUGHTER]

01:43:25.210 --> 01:43:29.960
Yet after a while, as is the
case with most relationships,

01:43:29.960 --> 01:43:32.230
the luster began to wear.

01:43:32.230 --> 01:43:33.720
It didn't take
long to discover we

01:43:33.720 --> 01:43:37.270
were captives of
a crazed romantic.

01:43:37.270 --> 01:43:40.260
Suddenly Harvard wanted to
put a label on everything.

01:43:40.260 --> 01:43:43.540
What is your concentration?

01:43:43.540 --> 01:43:45.040
The answer to this
question depended

01:43:45.040 --> 01:43:47.890
on each of our prior interests.

01:43:47.890 --> 01:43:52.036
Perhaps you want something
serious so you chose gov.

01:43:52.036 --> 01:43:54.370
[LAUGHTER]

01:43:54.370 --> 01:43:56.750
Maybe you wanted
something casual,

01:43:56.750 --> 01:43:58.610
so you chose
applied mathematics.

01:43:58.610 --> 01:44:01.280
[LAUGHTER]

01:44:01.280 --> 01:44:05.370
If you had a crush on governor
Chris Christie or Beyonce,

01:44:05.370 --> 01:44:07.370
you chose economics
because you're

01:44:07.370 --> 01:44:09.440
heard ec had even better curves.

01:44:09.440 --> 01:44:12.750
[LAUGHTER]

01:44:12.750 --> 01:44:15.540
But by junior year,
I started to doubt

01:44:15.540 --> 01:44:18.670
why ever fell in love with
Harvard in the first place.

01:44:18.670 --> 01:44:21.600
I no longer found backpack
checking in Lamont Library

01:44:21.600 --> 01:44:25.290
cute, and started to play the
game, how many books can I

01:44:25.290 --> 01:44:27.400
steal without the
security guard noticing?

01:44:27.400 --> 01:44:30.890
[LAUGHTER]

01:44:30.890 --> 01:44:34.630
Two course backs, a signed
copy of [INAUDIBLE] textbook,

01:44:34.630 --> 01:44:37.050
and an Orangina is
a personal best.

01:44:37.050 --> 01:44:39.320
[LAUGHTER]

01:44:39.320 --> 01:44:41.920
Then word got out we
might have cheated on her

01:44:41.920 --> 01:44:45.150
or at least collaborated
with multiple individuals,

01:44:45.150 --> 01:44:48.070
causing Harvard to read
through all of our emails.

01:44:48.070 --> 01:44:51.700
[LAUGHTER]

01:44:51.700 --> 01:44:54.440
Yet still with all
of Harvard's quirks,

01:44:54.440 --> 01:44:58.840
senior year reminded us
that time is fleeting.

01:44:58.840 --> 01:45:01.080
Oh, what you wouldn't
give now to be back

01:45:01.080 --> 01:45:03.900
with Harvard in the stacks
of Widener one last time.

01:45:06.640 --> 01:45:09.665
I myself have a memory
of discussing my grade

01:45:09.665 --> 01:45:14.150
with a TF in the stacks, only
to learn I couldn't get it up.

01:45:14.150 --> 01:45:16.002
[LAUGHTER]

01:45:19.250 --> 01:45:23.190
Perhaps you too
have fond memories.

01:45:23.190 --> 01:45:25.580
But this doesn't
need to be goodbye.

01:45:25.580 --> 01:45:28.240
And I don't believe
today is a break up.

01:45:28.240 --> 01:45:31.930
In fact, it looks
more like a wedding.

01:45:31.930 --> 01:45:33.740
I mean, our parents are here.

01:45:33.740 --> 01:45:34.950
They've paid quite the dowry.

01:45:34.950 --> 01:45:37.350
[LAUGHTER]

01:45:37.350 --> 01:45:40.055
And Harvard's reverse tiger mom
is still nowhere to be found.

01:45:40.055 --> 01:45:42.534
[LAUGHTER]

01:45:42.534 --> 01:45:44.950
And perhaps it's easy to think
that we're all marrying out

01:45:44.950 --> 01:45:48.910
of our league when we
look at Harvard's exes.

01:45:48.910 --> 01:45:52.320
I mean, just off the top of my
head I could name presidents.

01:45:52.320 --> 01:45:56.970
Henry David Thoreau, Bill Gates,
Tommy Lee Jones, and the Artist

01:45:56.970 --> 01:46:02.290
Formerly Known as-- and
still known as-- Yo Yo Ma.

01:46:02.290 --> 01:46:06.010
Yet with all of that in
mind, we must not forget,

01:46:06.010 --> 01:46:08.130
Harvard chose us too.

01:46:08.130 --> 01:46:12.480
She liked us enough to
put a one ring on it.

01:46:12.480 --> 01:46:14.180
It's not a one-sided
relationship

01:46:14.180 --> 01:46:16.950
like most of those we
knew in high school.

01:46:16.950 --> 01:46:21.920
Tomorrow we will leave,
but be bonded forever.

01:46:21.920 --> 01:46:26.077
My father, who is Mexican, which
really doesn't have anything

01:46:26.077 --> 01:46:27.535
to do with this
part of the story--

01:46:27.535 --> 01:46:29.884
[LAUGHTER]

01:46:33.330 --> 01:46:35.540
I just mention it, because
the last time I did,

01:46:35.540 --> 01:46:36.505
Harvard accepted me.

01:46:36.505 --> 01:46:38.254
[LAUGHTER]

01:46:47.218 --> 01:46:49.130
So I'll throw it
out there again.

01:46:49.130 --> 01:46:51.510
[LAUGHTER]

01:46:51.510 --> 01:46:55.610
He once told me, marry
the right person and life,

01:46:55.610 --> 01:46:58.440
no matter how difficult the
challenges you might face,

01:46:58.440 --> 01:47:00.840
will always be fun.

01:47:00.840 --> 01:47:03.660
I have no doubt our challenges
will get more serious than

01:47:03.660 --> 01:47:08.370
our complaints of having to walk
10 minutes to get to bio labs,

01:47:08.370 --> 01:47:11.170
dealing with getting snubbed
from Harvard's student model

01:47:11.170 --> 01:47:14.650
fashion show-- four
years in a row--

01:47:14.650 --> 01:47:18.260
[LAUGHTER]

01:47:18.260 --> 01:47:21.760
--probably because
you're too good looking.

01:47:21.760 --> 01:47:25.337
Or stomaching an
endangered fish.

01:47:25.337 --> 01:47:26.920
Seriously, that last
one's not a joke.

01:47:26.920 --> 01:47:27.610
Google it.

01:47:27.610 --> 01:47:31.100
S-W-A-I-- someone's got to
do something about that.

01:47:31.100 --> 01:47:33.240
[LAUGHTER]

01:47:33.240 --> 01:47:37.960
But through it all, Harvard
will be there with us.

01:47:37.960 --> 01:47:39.880
And even though we might
be marrying someone

01:47:39.880 --> 01:47:44.960
roughly 354 years older
than us, Harvard's vitality

01:47:44.960 --> 01:47:46.820
has never wavered.

01:47:46.820 --> 01:47:50.090
AKA, don't plan on getting
any of the endowment,

01:47:50.090 --> 01:47:51.350
you dirty gold diggers.

01:47:51.350 --> 01:47:55.450
[LAUGHTER]

01:47:55.450 --> 01:47:59.400
To conclude, I'd like to
congratulate the happy couple

01:47:59.400 --> 01:48:01.300
that is all of us
and all that we

01:48:01.300 --> 01:48:05.390
have gained in our four
years we've been together.

01:48:05.390 --> 01:48:07.740
Despite what those jealous
of our liberal arts schooling

01:48:07.740 --> 01:48:11.770
might say, truly think of
all the applicable gifts

01:48:11.770 --> 01:48:13.720
we have been given.

01:48:13.720 --> 01:48:15.720
I mean, just for
myself tomorrow,

01:48:15.720 --> 01:48:19.700
I graduate with a
Spanish citation,

01:48:19.700 --> 01:48:22.450
which means I can
legally hablas Espanol.

01:48:22.450 --> 01:48:24.329
[LAUGHTER]

01:48:28.280 --> 01:48:31.200
I got a degree in
economics, which

01:48:31.200 --> 01:48:33.760
means according to the
study I just conducted

01:48:33.760 --> 01:48:36.335
with the only other
econ alum up on stage,

01:48:36.335 --> 01:48:37.585
I'm going to be a billionaire.

01:48:37.585 --> 01:48:39.296
[LAUGHTER]

01:48:39.296 --> 01:48:40.260
And a woman.

01:48:40.260 --> 01:48:42.670
[LAUGHTER]

01:48:46.050 --> 01:48:48.330
Yes, I will be a billionaire.

01:48:48.330 --> 01:48:51.360
Provided, of course,
I download the Lean

01:48:51.360 --> 01:48:55.300
In audio book on my iPod
and immediately delete

01:48:55.300 --> 01:48:59.330
the contradictory message
delivered by Fat Joe's 2004 hip

01:48:59.330 --> 01:49:01.022
hop classic, Lean Back.

01:49:01.022 --> 01:49:03.432
[LAUGHTER]

01:49:06.330 --> 01:49:11.330
How Ms. Sandberg can refute Mr.
Joe's well articulated thesis

01:49:11.330 --> 01:49:15.650
of pulling up your pants,
doing the Rockaway,

01:49:15.650 --> 01:49:18.360
and proceeding to lean
back, lean back, lean back,

01:49:18.360 --> 01:49:22.710
is not my place to say.

01:49:22.710 --> 01:49:27.110
But I am sure she will
address such in her speech.

01:49:27.110 --> 01:49:31.840
And as if that wasn't
enough, I get a secondary

01:49:31.840 --> 01:49:34.890
in neurobiology,
which means I only

01:49:34.890 --> 01:49:37.225
need to operate on brains
if someone who concentrated

01:49:37.225 --> 01:49:38.695
in neurobiology isn't around.

01:49:38.695 --> 01:49:40.758
[LAUGHTER]

01:49:43.470 --> 01:49:45.700
Your gifts might be these.

01:49:45.700 --> 01:49:48.400
Most likely even
better than these.

01:49:48.400 --> 01:49:50.110
The point is, we've
worked hard to get

01:49:50.110 --> 01:49:54.160
here, even harder
to get here today.

01:49:54.160 --> 01:49:56.060
And I'd wager once we
are thrown into a world

01:49:56.060 --> 01:49:59.360
without great inflation,
probably our hardest tomorrow.

01:49:59.360 --> 01:50:00.680
[LAUGHTER]

01:50:00.680 --> 01:50:03.290
But we are ready.

01:50:03.290 --> 01:50:07.690
With our fair spouse at
our side, we say, I do.

01:50:07.690 --> 01:50:10.492
And before
consummation tomorrow--

01:50:10.492 --> 01:50:12.897
[LAUGHTER]

01:50:15.790 --> 01:50:18.080
--before consummation I'd
like to propose a toast.

01:50:18.080 --> 01:50:21.915
[LAUGHTER]

01:50:21.915 --> 01:50:23.415
I thought there was
champagne served

01:50:23.415 --> 01:50:24.570
at these things
for all of you too.

01:50:24.570 --> 01:50:25.070
I'm sorry.

01:50:25.070 --> 01:50:27.440
[LAUGHTER]

01:50:27.440 --> 01:50:30.680
May we live our
lives not comparing

01:50:30.680 --> 01:50:34.370
to those that came before
our class or those that

01:50:34.370 --> 01:50:39.660
may come after, but rather
cherish in the comfort knowing

01:50:39.660 --> 01:50:43.080
that we will have this
place that we love forever

01:50:43.080 --> 01:50:47.470
in our hearts, for the rest
of our lives, till death do us

01:50:47.470 --> 01:50:48.320
part.

01:50:48.320 --> 01:50:50.643
Cheers and congratulations
class of 2014.

01:50:50.643 --> 01:50:51.629
Thank you, Mom.

01:50:51.629 --> 01:50:52.615
Thank you, Dad.

