Because if memory serves,
some of your classmates

01:54:53.610 --> 01:54:56.483
had too many scorpion bowls
at the Kong last night

01:54:56.483 --> 01:54:59.800
and aren't with us today.

01:54:59.800 --> 01:55:02.910
Given the weather, the one
thing Harvard hasn't figured out

01:55:02.910 --> 01:55:05.880
how to control, some of
your other classmates

01:55:05.880 --> 01:55:08.290
are someplace warm
with a hot cocoa,

01:55:08.290 --> 01:55:11.060
so you have many reasons
to feel proud of yourselves

01:55:11.060 --> 01:55:14.090
as you sit here today.

01:55:14.090 --> 01:55:16.380
Congratulations to your parents.

01:55:16.380 --> 01:55:19.890
You have spent a lot of
money so your child can

01:55:19.890 --> 01:55:22.570
say she went to a small
school near Boston.

01:55:22.570 --> 01:55:25.200
[LAUGHTER]

01:55:25.200 --> 01:55:27.540
And thank you to
the class of 2014

01:55:27.540 --> 01:55:29.940
for inviting me to be
part of your celebration.

01:55:29.940 --> 01:55:31.960
It means a great deal to me.

01:55:31.960 --> 01:55:36.170
And looking at the list of past
speakers was a little daunting.

01:55:36.170 --> 01:55:38.610
I can't be as funny
as Amy Poehler,

01:55:38.610 --> 01:55:40.680
but I'm going to be
funnier than Mother Teresa.

01:55:40.680 --> 01:55:43.155
[LAUGHTER]

01:55:46.630 --> 01:55:50.700
25 years ago, a man named Dave
I did not know at the time

01:55:50.700 --> 01:55:52.790
but who would one day
become my husband,

01:55:52.790 --> 01:55:55.610
was sitting where you
are sitting today.

01:55:55.610 --> 01:56:00.210
23 years ago, I was sitting
where you are sitting today.

01:56:00.210 --> 01:56:02.620
David and I are back this
weekend with our amazing son

01:56:02.620 --> 01:56:05.490
and daughter to
celebrate his reunion.

01:56:05.490 --> 01:56:08.570
And we both share
the same sentiment.

01:56:08.570 --> 01:56:10.650
Harvard has a good
basketball team.

01:56:10.650 --> 01:56:13.750
[LAUGHTER]

01:56:13.750 --> 01:56:17.770
Standing here in the yard brings
memories flooding back for me.

01:56:17.770 --> 01:56:21.610
I arrived here from
Miami in the fall of 1987

01:56:21.610 --> 01:56:26.080
with big hopes and
even bigger hair.

01:56:26.080 --> 01:56:29.110
I was assigned to live in one
of Harvard's historic monuments

01:56:29.110 --> 01:56:31.066
to great architecture, Canaday.

01:56:31.066 --> 01:56:35.470
[LAUGHTER]

01:56:35.470 --> 01:56:37.620
My go-to outfit-- and
I'm not making this up--

01:56:37.620 --> 01:56:41.040
was a jean skirt, white
leg warmers and sneakers,

01:56:41.040 --> 01:56:43.950
and a Florida sweatshirt,
because my parents who

01:56:43.950 --> 01:56:46.370
were here with me then as
they're here with me now,

01:56:46.370 --> 01:56:48.850
told me everyone would
think it was awesome

01:56:48.850 --> 01:56:50.120
that I was from Florida.

01:56:50.120 --> 01:56:52.479
[LAUGHTER]

01:56:52.479 --> 01:56:53.895
At least we didn't
have Instagram.

01:56:56.930 --> 01:57:00.260
For me, Harvard was
a series of firsts.

01:57:00.260 --> 01:57:04.111
My first winter coat-- we
didn't need those in Miami--

01:57:04.111 --> 01:57:07.190
my first 10 page paper--
they didn't assign those

01:57:07.190 --> 01:57:12.350
in my high school-- my first C,
after which my proctor told me

01:57:12.350 --> 01:57:15.570
that she was on the admissions
committee, and I got

01:57:15.570 --> 01:57:18.070
admitted to Harvard
for my personality, not

01:57:18.070 --> 01:57:19.100
my academic potential.

01:57:22.490 --> 01:57:24.840
The first person I ever
met from boarding school--

01:57:24.840 --> 01:57:28.820
I thought that was for
really troubled kids--

01:57:28.820 --> 01:57:30.460
the first person I
ever met who shared

01:57:30.460 --> 01:57:32.780
a name with a whole
building, or so I

01:57:32.780 --> 01:57:34.580
met when the first
classmate I met

01:57:34.580 --> 01:57:38.130
was Sarah Wigglesworth,
who bore no relation at all

01:57:38.130 --> 01:57:40.440
to the dorm, which
would've been nice to know

01:57:40.440 --> 01:57:43.170
at that very
intimidating moment.

01:57:43.170 --> 01:57:45.630
But then I went
on to meet others.

01:57:45.630 --> 01:57:50.459
Frances Strauss, James Weld,
Jessica Science Center [? B. ?]

01:57:50.459 --> 01:57:52.924
[LAUGHTER]

01:57:56.880 --> 01:58:01.180
My first love, my
first heartbreak,

01:58:01.180 --> 01:58:04.510
the first time I
realized I love to learn,

01:58:04.510 --> 01:58:06.410
and the first and
very last time I

01:58:06.410 --> 01:58:08.946
saw anyone read
anything in Latin.

01:58:08.946 --> 01:58:11.790
[LAUGHTER]

01:58:11.790 --> 01:58:14.090
When I sat in your seat
all those years ago,

01:58:14.090 --> 01:58:16.050
I knew exactly
where I was headed.

01:58:16.050 --> 01:58:17.550
I had it all planned out.

01:58:17.550 --> 01:58:20.400
I was going to the World Bank
to work on global poverty,

01:58:20.400 --> 01:58:22.052
then I would go to
law school, then

01:58:22.052 --> 01:58:23.885
I would spend my life
working in a nonprofit

01:58:23.885 --> 01:58:25.820
or in the government.

01:58:25.820 --> 01:58:27.530
At Harvard's
commencement tomorrow,

01:58:27.530 --> 01:58:29.670
as your dean
described, each school

01:58:29.670 --> 01:58:31.890
is going to stand up
and graduate together--

01:58:31.890 --> 01:58:35.210
the college, the law school,
the med school, and so on.

01:58:35.210 --> 01:58:39.630
At my graduation, my class
cheered for the Ph.D. students

01:58:39.630 --> 01:58:42.320
and then booed the
business school.

01:58:42.320 --> 01:58:45.960
Business school seemed
like such a sellout.

01:58:45.960 --> 01:58:48.720
18 months later I applied
to business school.

01:58:48.720 --> 01:58:50.230
[LAUGHTER]

01:58:50.230 --> 01:58:51.760
It wasn't that was
wrong about what

01:58:51.760 --> 01:58:53.760
I would do decades
after graduating.

01:58:53.760 --> 01:58:57.484
I had it wrong a year
and a half later.

01:58:57.484 --> 01:58:58.900
And even if I could
have predicted

01:58:58.900 --> 01:59:00.920
I would one day work
in the private sector,

01:59:00.920 --> 01:59:03.570
I never could have
predicted Facebook.

01:59:03.570 --> 01:59:06.050
Because there was no internet.

01:59:06.050 --> 01:59:08.070
And Mark Zuckerberg was
in elementary school.

01:59:08.070 --> 01:59:10.790
[LAUGHTER]

01:59:10.790 --> 01:59:12.830
Already wearing his hoodie.

01:59:12.830 --> 01:59:16.330
[LAUGHTER]

01:59:16.330 --> 01:59:20.220
Not locking into a
path too early gave me

01:59:20.220 --> 01:59:23.600
an opportunity to go into a
new and life changing field.

01:59:23.600 --> 01:59:26.540
And for those of you think I
owe everything to good luck,

01:59:26.540 --> 01:59:28.730
after Canaday, I got quadded.

01:59:28.730 --> 01:59:29.688
[LAUGHTER AND CHEERS]

01:59:29.688 --> 01:59:30.646
What's up, Adam?

01:59:35.440 --> 01:59:37.830
There is no straight
path from your seat

01:59:37.830 --> 01:59:39.250
today to where you are going.

01:59:39.250 --> 01:59:41.010
Don't try to draw that line.

01:59:41.010 --> 01:59:44.480
You will not just get it wrong,
you'll miss big opportunities.

01:59:44.480 --> 01:59:46.010
And I mean big.

01:59:46.010 --> 01:59:47.490
Like the internet.

01:59:47.490 --> 01:59:50.250
[LAUGHTER]

01:59:50.250 --> 01:59:52.710
Careers are not ladders--
those days are long

01:59:52.710 --> 01:59:54.630
gone-- but jungle gyms.

01:59:54.630 --> 01:59:57.366
Don't just move up and
down, don't just look up.

01:59:57.366 --> 02:00:00.610
Look backwards,
sideways, around corners.

02:00:00.610 --> 02:00:02.580
Your career and
your life will have

02:00:02.580 --> 02:00:05.420
starts and stops
and zigs and zags.

02:00:05.420 --> 02:00:09.360
Don't stress out about the white
space, the path you can't draw,

02:00:09.360 --> 02:00:11.387
because therein lies
both the surprises

02:00:11.387 --> 02:00:12.303
and the opportunities.

02:00:14.900 --> 02:00:16.910
As you open yourself
up to possibility,

02:00:16.910 --> 02:00:20.110
the most important thing
I can tell you today

02:00:20.110 --> 02:00:23.620
is to open yourself
up to honesty.

02:00:23.620 --> 02:00:26.360
To telling the
truth to each other,

02:00:26.360 --> 02:00:29.850
to being honest with
yourselves, and to being

02:00:29.850 --> 02:00:33.380
honest about the
world we live in.

02:00:33.380 --> 02:00:35.590
If you watch children
you will immediately

02:00:35.590 --> 02:00:37.820
notice how honest they are.

02:00:37.820 --> 02:00:41.540
My friend Betsy was pregnant and
her son, or their second child.

02:00:41.540 --> 02:00:43.720
Son Sam was five,
he wanted to know

02:00:43.720 --> 02:00:45.760
where the baby was in her body.

02:00:45.760 --> 02:00:49.630
So he asked Mommy, are the
baby's arms in your arms?

02:00:49.630 --> 02:00:51.300
And she said, no, no, Sam.

02:00:51.300 --> 02:00:52.270
Baby's in my tummy.

02:00:52.270 --> 02:00:54.300
Whole baby.

02:00:54.300 --> 02:00:57.610
Mom, are the baby's
legs in your legs?

02:00:57.610 --> 02:00:59.050
No Sam.

02:00:59.050 --> 02:01:01.610
Whole baby's in my tummy.

02:01:01.610 --> 02:01:04.320
Then mommy, what's
growing in your butt?

02:01:04.320 --> 02:01:07.070
[LAUGHTER]

02:01:12.340 --> 02:01:15.960
As adults, we are almost
never this honest,

02:01:15.960 --> 02:01:18.060
and that can be a
very good thing.

02:01:18.060 --> 02:01:20.000
When I was pregnant
with our first child

02:01:20.000 --> 02:01:23.490
I asked my husband Dave if
my butt was getting big.

02:01:23.490 --> 02:01:27.460
At first he didn't answer but
I pressed, so he said, yeah.

02:01:27.460 --> 02:01:29.370
A little.

02:01:29.370 --> 02:01:31.600
For years my sister-in-law
said about him

02:01:31.600 --> 02:01:34.220
what people will now say about
you for the rest of your life

02:01:34.220 --> 02:01:38.300
when you do something dumb:
and that guy went to Harvard.

02:01:38.300 --> 02:01:42.740
[LAUGHTER]

02:01:42.740 --> 02:01:45.220
Hearing the truth at
different times along the way

02:01:45.220 --> 02:01:46.530
would have helped me.

02:01:46.530 --> 02:01:48.390
I would not have
admitted it easily when

02:01:48.390 --> 02:01:50.030
I sat where you sit.

02:01:50.030 --> 02:01:53.450
But when I graduated I was much
more worried about my love life

02:01:53.450 --> 02:01:54.930
than my career.

02:01:54.930 --> 02:01:57.130
I thought I only had a
few years, very limited

02:01:57.130 --> 02:02:02.820
time, to find one of the good
guys before they were all taken

02:02:02.820 --> 02:02:04.510
or I got too old.

02:02:04.510 --> 02:02:06.890
So I moved to D.C.,
I met a good guy,

02:02:06.890 --> 02:02:11.960
and I got married at the
nearly decrepit age of 24.

02:02:11.960 --> 02:02:14.590
I married a wonderful
man, but I had no business

02:02:14.590 --> 02:02:15.940
making that kind of commitment.

02:02:15.940 --> 02:02:18.310
I didn't know who I was
or who I wanted to be.

02:02:21.220 --> 02:02:23.880
My marriage fell apart
within a year, something

02:02:23.880 --> 02:02:27.210
that was really embarrassing
and painful at the time.

02:02:27.210 --> 02:02:30.791
And it did not help that so many
friends came up to me and said,

02:02:30.791 --> 02:02:31.540
I never knew that.

02:02:31.540 --> 02:02:33.081
Never thought that
was going to work.

02:02:33.081 --> 02:02:36.230
Or, I knew you two weren't
right for each other.

02:02:36.230 --> 02:02:39.450
No one had managed to say
anything like that to me

02:02:39.450 --> 02:02:41.580
before I marched
down an aisle when

02:02:41.580 --> 02:02:44.856
it would have been
far more useful.

02:02:44.856 --> 02:02:47.230
And as I lived through those
painful months of separation

02:02:47.230 --> 02:02:50.130
and divorce, boy
did I wish they had.

02:02:50.130 --> 02:02:53.800
And boy, did I wish
I had asked them.

02:02:53.800 --> 02:02:55.790
At the same time in
my professional life,

02:02:55.790 --> 02:02:57.440
someone did speak up.

02:02:57.440 --> 02:02:59.680
My first boss out of
college was Lant Pritchett,

02:02:59.680 --> 02:03:01.520
an economist who
teaches at the Kennedy

02:03:01.520 --> 02:03:03.850
School who's here with us today.

02:03:03.850 --> 02:03:06.210
After I deferred law
school for the second time,

02:03:06.210 --> 02:03:08.040
Lant sat me down
and said, I don't

02:03:08.040 --> 02:03:10.320
think you should go
to law school at all.

02:03:10.320 --> 02:03:12.264
I don't think you want
to go to law school.

02:03:12.264 --> 02:03:13.930
I think you think you
should because you

02:03:13.930 --> 02:03:16.900
told your parents you
would many years ago.

02:03:16.900 --> 02:03:18.740
He noted that he
had never once heard

02:03:18.740 --> 02:03:20.720
me talk about the law
with any interest.

02:03:23.380 --> 02:03:26.300
I know how hard it can be to
be honest with each other.

02:03:26.300 --> 02:03:28.070
Even your closest
friends, even when

02:03:28.070 --> 02:03:30.520
they're about to make
serious mistakes.

02:03:30.520 --> 02:03:32.800
But I bet sitting
here today, you

02:03:32.800 --> 02:03:36.040
know your closest friends'
strengths, weaknesses,

02:03:36.040 --> 02:03:38.360
what cliff they might drive off.

02:03:38.360 --> 02:03:42.360
And I bet for the most
part you've never told them

02:03:42.360 --> 02:03:44.790
and they've never asked.

02:03:44.790 --> 02:03:46.380
Ask them.

02:03:46.380 --> 02:03:49.430
Ask them for the truth,
because it will help you.

02:03:49.430 --> 02:03:51.910
And when they answer
honestly, know

02:03:51.910 --> 02:03:55.560
that that's what makes
them real friends.

02:03:55.560 --> 02:03:57.890
Asking for feedback is
a really important habit

02:03:57.890 --> 02:04:01.370
to get into as you leave
the structure of the school

02:04:01.370 --> 02:04:03.910
calendar and exams
and grades behind.

02:04:03.910 --> 02:04:06.330
On many jobs, if you want
to know how you're doing,

02:04:06.330 --> 02:04:08.270
you're going to have
to ask, and then you're

02:04:08.270 --> 02:04:10.954
going to have to listen
without getting defensive.

02:04:10.954 --> 02:04:11.620
Take it from me.

02:04:11.620 --> 02:04:13.980
Listening to criticism
is never fun,

02:04:13.980 --> 02:04:17.240
but it's the only
way we can improve.

02:04:17.240 --> 02:04:19.330
A few years ago, Mark
Zuckerberg decided

02:04:19.330 --> 02:04:21.360
he wanted to learn Chinese.

02:04:21.360 --> 02:04:23.430
And in order to
practice, he started

02:04:23.430 --> 02:04:25.680
trying to have work meetings
with some of our Facebook

02:04:25.680 --> 02:04:27.990
colleagues who are
native speakers.

02:04:27.990 --> 02:04:30.990
Now you would think his very
limited language skills would

02:04:30.990 --> 02:04:34.200
keep these conversations
from being useful.

02:04:34.200 --> 02:04:36.350
One day he asked a
woman who was there

02:04:36.350 --> 02:04:38.990
how it was going, how
did she like Facebook?

02:04:38.990 --> 02:04:42.120
She answered with a long and
pretty complicated sentence.

02:04:42.120 --> 02:04:44.880
So he said, you
know, simpler please.

02:04:44.880 --> 02:04:47.470
She spoke again.

02:04:47.470 --> 02:04:49.270
Simpler please.

02:04:49.270 --> 02:04:51.080
This went back and
forth a couple of times,

02:04:51.080 --> 02:04:55.438
so she just blurted out of
frustration, my manager is bad.

02:04:55.438 --> 02:04:58.651
[LAUGHTER]

02:04:58.651 --> 02:05:01.740
That he understood.

02:05:01.740 --> 02:05:05.800
So often the truth is sacrificed
to conflict avoidance,

02:05:05.800 --> 02:05:07.790
or by the time we
speak the truth,

02:05:07.790 --> 02:05:11.810
we've used so many caveats and
preambles the message totally

02:05:11.810 --> 02:05:12.930
gets lost.

02:05:12.930 --> 02:05:16.180
So as you ask each other for
the truth and other people,

02:05:16.180 --> 02:05:19.390
can you elicit it in
simple and clear language?

02:05:19.390 --> 02:05:21.505
And when you speak
your truth, can you

02:05:21.505 --> 02:05:23.320
use simple and clear language?

02:05:30.250 --> 02:05:33.180
As hard as it is to be
honest with other people,

02:05:33.180 --> 02:05:36.710
it can be even more difficult
to be honest with ourselves.

02:05:36.710 --> 02:05:40.360
For years after I had children
I would say pretty often,

02:05:40.360 --> 02:05:44.060
I don't feel guilty working
even when no one asked.

02:05:44.060 --> 02:05:46.122
Someone might say, Sheryl,
how's your day today?

02:05:46.122 --> 02:05:47.080
And I would say, great.

02:05:47.080 --> 02:05:49.390
I don't feel guilty working.

02:05:49.390 --> 02:05:52.170
Or, do I need a sweater?

02:05:52.170 --> 02:05:54.990
Yes, it's
unpredictably freezing.

02:05:54.990 --> 02:05:57.750
And I don't feel guilty working.

02:05:57.750 --> 02:06:01.640
I was kind of like a
parrot with issues.

02:06:01.640 --> 02:06:04.430
Then one day on the treadmill
I was reading this article

02:06:04.430 --> 02:06:07.300
in the sociology journal about
how people don't start out

02:06:07.300 --> 02:06:08.570
lying to other people.

02:06:08.570 --> 02:06:10.370
They start out
lying to themselves.

02:06:10.370 --> 02:06:12.640
And the things we
repeat most frequently

02:06:12.640 --> 02:06:14.590
are often those lies.

02:06:14.590 --> 02:06:17.460
So as sweat was pouring down my
face I started wondering, well,

02:06:17.460 --> 02:06:19.500
what do I repeat
pretty frequently?

02:06:19.500 --> 02:06:23.240
And I realized, I
feel guilty working.

02:06:23.240 --> 02:06:26.730
I then did a lot of research
and I spent an entire year

02:06:26.730 --> 02:06:29.330
with my dear friend Nell
Scovell writing a book,

02:06:29.330 --> 02:06:32.170
talking about how I was
thinking and feeling.

02:06:32.170 --> 02:06:35.510
And I'm so grateful that so
many women around the world

02:06:35.510 --> 02:06:37.670
connected to it.

02:06:37.670 --> 02:06:40.845
My book, of course, was
called Fifty Shades of Grey.

02:06:40.845 --> 02:06:43.960
[LAUGHTER]

02:06:43.960 --> 02:06:46.520
I can see a lot of you
connected to it as well.

02:06:46.520 --> 02:06:50.030
[LAUGHTER]

02:06:50.030 --> 02:06:52.240
We have even more
work to do in being

02:06:52.240 --> 02:06:55.090
honest about the
world we live in.

02:06:55.090 --> 02:06:58.150
We don't always see the hard
truths, and once we see them,

02:06:58.150 --> 02:07:01.340
we don't always have the
courage to speak out.

02:07:01.340 --> 02:07:03.740
When my classmates
and I were in college

02:07:03.740 --> 02:07:07.170
we thought the fight for gender
equality was won, it was over.

02:07:07.170 --> 02:07:10.930
Sure, most of the leaders
in every industry were men,

02:07:10.930 --> 02:07:13.910
but we thought changing that
was just a matter of time.

02:07:13.910 --> 02:07:18.120
Lamont Library right over
there, one generation before us,

02:07:18.120 --> 02:07:20.260
didn't let women
through its doors.

02:07:20.260 --> 02:07:23.510
But by the time we sat in your
seats, everything was equal.

02:07:23.510 --> 02:07:26.500
Harvard and Radcliffe
was fully integrated.

02:07:26.500 --> 02:07:29.265
We didn't need feminism
because we were already equals.

02:07:31.920 --> 02:07:33.870
We were wrong.

02:07:33.870 --> 02:07:35.720
I was wrong.

02:07:35.720 --> 02:07:40.800
The world was not equal then,
and it is not equal now.

02:07:40.800 --> 02:07:43.960
I think nowadays we
don't just hide ourselves

02:07:43.960 --> 02:07:47.640
from the hard truths and shut
our eyes to the inequities,

02:07:47.640 --> 02:07:51.170
but we suffer from the
tyranny of low expectations.

02:07:51.170 --> 02:07:53.630
In the last election cycle
in the United States,

02:07:53.630 --> 02:07:56.170
women won 20% of
the Senate seats.

02:07:56.170 --> 02:07:58.010
And all the headlines
kept screaming out,

02:07:58.010 --> 02:08:01.270
women take over the Senate,
women take over the Senate.

02:08:01.270 --> 02:08:04.230
I felt like screaming back,
wait a minute everyone.

02:08:04.230 --> 02:08:08.140
50% of the population
getting 20% of the seats?

02:08:08.140 --> 02:08:10.100
That's not a takeover.

02:08:10.100 --> 02:08:13.290
That's an embarrassment.

02:08:13.290 --> 02:08:18.350
Just a few months ago this year,
a very well respected and well

02:08:18.350 --> 02:08:20.950
known business executive
in Silicon Valley

02:08:20.950 --> 02:08:25.360
invited me to give a speech
to his club on social media.

02:08:25.360 --> 02:08:27.470
I'd been to this club a
few months before when

02:08:27.470 --> 02:08:30.020
I'd been invited for
a friend's birthday.

02:08:30.020 --> 02:08:31.380
It was a beautiful building.

02:08:31.380 --> 02:08:33.540
And I was wandering
around looking at it,

02:08:33.540 --> 02:08:36.520
looking for the women's room,
when a staff member informed

02:08:36.520 --> 02:08:39.790
me very firmly that the
ladies' room was over there,

02:08:39.790 --> 02:08:41.700
and I should be sure
not to go upstairs

02:08:41.700 --> 02:08:45.390
because women are never
allowed in this building.

02:08:45.390 --> 02:08:47.370
I didn't realize I was
in an all-male club

02:08:47.370 --> 02:08:49.030
until that minute.

02:08:49.030 --> 02:08:50.820
I spent the rest of
the night wondering

02:08:50.820 --> 02:08:53.090
what I was doing there,
wondering what everyone

02:08:53.090 --> 02:08:56.140
else was doing there, wondering
if any of my friends in San

02:08:56.140 --> 02:09:01.000
Francisco would invited me
to a party at a club that

02:09:01.000 --> 02:09:05.140
didn't allow blacks or
Jews or Asians or gays.

02:09:05.140 --> 02:09:07.380
Being invited to give a
business speech at this club

02:09:07.380 --> 02:09:09.280
hit me as even more
egregious, because you

02:09:09.280 --> 02:09:11.000
couldn't claim that
it was only social.

02:09:11.000 --> 02:09:12.700
Business wasn't done there.

02:09:12.700 --> 02:09:15.530
My first thought was, really?

02:09:15.530 --> 02:09:16.450
Really?

02:09:16.450 --> 02:09:18.760
A year after Lean
In, this dude thought

02:09:18.760 --> 02:09:22.730
it was a good idea to invite me
to give a speech to his literal

02:09:22.730 --> 02:09:25.700
all boys club.

02:09:25.700 --> 02:09:27.320
And he wasn't alone.

02:09:27.320 --> 02:09:31.150
There was an entire committee
of well-respected businessmen

02:09:31.150 --> 02:09:35.660
who joined him in issuing
this kind invitation.

02:09:35.660 --> 02:09:38.210
To paraphrase Groucho
Marx-- and don't worry,

02:09:38.210 --> 02:09:41.260
I won't try to do
the voice-- I don't

02:09:41.260 --> 02:09:44.810
want to speak at any club that
won't have me as a member.

02:09:44.810 --> 02:09:47.530
So I said no, and I did
it in a way I probably

02:09:47.530 --> 02:09:49.920
wouldn't have even
five years before.

02:09:49.920 --> 02:09:52.260
I wrote a long and
passionate email

02:09:52.260 --> 02:09:55.890
arguing that they should
change their policies.

02:09:55.890 --> 02:09:58.520
They thanked me for
my prompt response

02:09:58.520 --> 02:10:03.800
and wrote that perhaps things
will eventually change.

02:10:03.800 --> 02:10:07.370
Our expectations are too low.

02:10:07.370 --> 02:10:10.385
Eventually needs to
become immediately.

02:10:13.210 --> 02:10:15.610
[APPLAUSE]

02:10:21.870 --> 02:10:24.180
We need to see the truth
and speak the truth.

02:10:24.180 --> 02:10:25.970
We tolerate
discrimination and we

02:10:25.970 --> 02:10:28.240
pretend that
opportunity is equal.

02:10:28.240 --> 02:10:30.830
Yes, we elected an African
American president,

02:10:30.830 --> 02:10:33.430
but racism is pervasive still.

02:10:33.430 --> 02:10:37.430
Yes, there are women who run
Fortune 500 companies-- 5%

02:10:37.430 --> 02:10:40.370
to be precise-- but
our road there is still

02:10:40.370 --> 02:10:43.700
paved with words
like pushy and bossy,

02:10:43.700 --> 02:10:48.040
while our male peers are
leaders and results focused.

02:10:48.040 --> 02:10:51.390
African American women have to
prove that they're not angry.

02:10:51.390 --> 02:10:55.850
Latinas risk being
branded fiery hot heads.

02:10:55.850 --> 02:10:58.490
A group of Asian American
women and men at Facebook

02:10:58.490 --> 02:11:01.950
wore pins one day that said, I
may or may not be good at math.

02:11:05.470 --> 02:11:08.360
Yes, Harvard has
a woman president.

02:11:08.360 --> 02:11:10.160
And in two years
the United States

02:11:10.160 --> 02:11:11.910
may have a woman president.

02:11:11.910 --> 02:11:15.730
[CHEERS]

02:11:15.730 --> 02:11:17.980
But in order to get
there, Hillary Clinton

02:11:17.980 --> 02:11:23.370
is going to have to overcome
two very real obstacles, unknown

02:11:23.370 --> 02:11:29.502
and often ununderstood gender
bias, and even worse, a degree

02:11:29.502 --> 02:11:30.200
from Yale.

02:11:30.200 --> 02:11:34.390
[LAUGHTER]

02:11:34.390 --> 02:11:38.210
You can challenge stereotypes,
both subtle and obvious.

02:11:38.210 --> 02:11:41.880
At Facebook we have posters
around the wall to inspire us.

02:11:41.880 --> 02:11:44.560
Done is better than perfect,
fortune favors the bold,

02:11:44.560 --> 02:11:46.760
what would you do if
you weren't afraid?

02:11:46.760 --> 02:11:49.410
My new favorite:
nothing at Facebook

02:11:49.410 --> 02:11:51.780
is someone else's problem.

02:11:51.780 --> 02:11:54.330
I hope you feel that
way about the problems

02:11:54.330 --> 02:11:56.430
you see in the world
because they are not

02:11:56.430 --> 02:11:58.450
someone else's problem.

02:11:58.450 --> 02:12:01.630
Gender inequality harms
men along with women.

02:12:01.630 --> 02:12:04.550
Racism hurts whites
along with minorities.

02:12:04.550 --> 02:12:08.280
And the lack of equal
opportunity keeps all of us

02:12:08.280 --> 02:12:09.980
from fulfilling
our true potential.

02:12:13.210 --> 02:12:17.384
So as you graduate today, I want
to put some pressure on you.

02:12:17.384 --> 02:12:18.800
I want to put some
pressure on you

02:12:18.800 --> 02:12:22.720
to acknowledge the hard
truths, not shy away from them,

02:12:22.720 --> 02:12:25.900
and when you see
them to address them.

02:12:25.900 --> 02:12:28.430
The first time I
spoke out about what

02:12:28.430 --> 02:12:30.730
it was like to be a
woman in the workforce

02:12:30.730 --> 02:12:33.650
was less than five years ago.

02:12:33.650 --> 02:12:36.370
That means that for
18 years from where

02:12:36.370 --> 02:12:39.830
you sit to where I
stand, my silence

02:12:39.830 --> 02:12:44.020
implies that everything was OK.

02:12:44.020 --> 02:12:46.600
You can do better than I did.

02:12:46.600 --> 02:12:50.370
And I mean that so sincerely.

02:12:50.370 --> 02:12:54.660
At the same time I wanted to
take some pressure off you.

02:12:54.660 --> 02:12:56.360
Sitting here today
you don't have

02:12:56.360 --> 02:12:58.010
to know what career
you want or how

02:12:58.010 --> 02:13:00.190
to get the career
you might want.

02:13:00.190 --> 02:13:02.680
Leaning in does not
mean your path will

02:13:02.680 --> 02:13:04.900
be straight or smooth,
and most people

02:13:04.900 --> 02:13:08.110
who make great contributions
start way later

02:13:08.110 --> 02:13:09.910
than Mark Zuckerberg.

02:13:09.910 --> 02:13:13.210
Find a jungle gym you want to
play on and start climbing.

02:13:13.210 --> 02:13:16.870
Not only will you figure out
what you want to do eventually,

02:13:16.870 --> 02:13:20.350
but once you do,
you will crush it.

02:13:20.350 --> 02:13:24.750
Looking at you all here
today I am filled with hope.

02:13:24.750 --> 02:13:29.890
All of you were admitted to
a small school near Boston,

02:13:29.890 --> 02:13:32.870
either for your academic
potential, your personality,

02:13:32.870 --> 02:13:35.410
or both.

02:13:35.410 --> 02:13:37.680
You've had your
firsts, whether it's

02:13:37.680 --> 02:13:41.860
a winter coat, a love, or
a C. You've learned more

02:13:41.860 --> 02:13:44.940
about who you are and
who you want to be.

02:13:44.940 --> 02:13:48.040
And most importantly,
you've experienced

02:13:48.040 --> 02:13:50.100
the power of community.

02:13:50.100 --> 02:13:54.130
You know that while you are
extraordinary on your own,

02:13:54.130 --> 02:13:59.670
we are all stronger and
can be louder together.

02:13:59.670 --> 02:14:04.110
I know that you will
never forget Harvard,

02:14:04.110 --> 02:14:06.840
and Harvard will
never forget you.

02:14:06.840 --> 02:14:09.290
Especially during the
next fundraising drive.

02:14:09.290 --> 02:14:12.930
[LAUGHTER]

02:14:12.930 --> 02:14:17.250
Tomorrow you all become part
of a lifelong community which

02:14:17.250 --> 02:14:21.110
offers truly great opportunity,
and therefore comes

02:14:21.110 --> 02:14:23.640
with real obligation.

02:14:23.640 --> 02:14:26.970
You can make the world
fairer for everyone.

02:14:26.970 --> 02:14:30.900
Expect honesty from
yourself and each other.

02:14:30.900 --> 02:14:37.200
Demand and create truly equal
opportunity, not eventually,

02:14:37.200 --> 02:14:39.450
but now.

02:14:39.450 --> 02:14:41.640
And tomorrow, by
the way, you get

02:14:41.640 --> 02:14:45.590
something Mark Zuckerberg does
not have: a Harvard degree.

02:14:45.590 --> 02:14:46.770
Congratulations everyone.

02:14:46.770 --> 02:14:49.235
[APPLAUSE]

02:15:05.879 --> 02:15:06.920
Thank you so much Sheryl.

02:15:06.920 --> 02:15:08.560
That was wonderful.

02:15:08.560 --> 02:15:10.270
Hello everyone.

02:15:10.270 --> 02:15:12.390
My name is Alicia Johnson,
and I have the pleasure

02:15:12.390 --> 02:15:14.681
of serving as the house
representative of Quincy House.

02:15:14.681 --> 02:15:17.600
[CHEERS]

02:15:17.600 --> 02:15:20.205
My name is Sharon Carlson and
I am the house representative

02:15:20.205 --> 02:15:21.420
for Elliot.

02:15:21.420 --> 02:15:23.270
[CHEERS]

02:15:23.270 --> 02:15:27.090
Together we have the honor
of introducing the class ode.

02:15:27.090 --> 02:15:29.690
Each year, members of the
class have the opportunity

02:15:29.690 --> 02:15:32.307
to write two verses in
the tune of Fair Harvard

02:15:32.307 --> 02:15:34.682
and compete for the chance to
present their opus on Class

02:15:34.682 --> 02:15:35.890
Day.

02:15:35.890 --> 02:15:40.550
While there are more than
1,600 different class

02:15:40.550 --> 02:15:43.290
of 2014 experiences,
the class ode

02:15:43.290 --> 02:15:45.520
strives to find
our common strands

02:15:45.520 --> 02:15:48.250
and create a piece of work
that we can all relate to.

02:15:48.250 --> 02:15:51.540
From late nights at Lamont to
even later nights at the Quincy

02:15:51.540 --> 02:15:54.440
Grill, we have been through
a lot during our time here,

02:15:54.440 --> 02:15:56.680
and the class ode creates
an opportunity for us

02:15:56.680 --> 02:15:59.830
to celebrate our class and
experienced through song,

02:15:59.830 --> 02:16:02.420
allowing the class
of 2014 to live on,

02:16:02.420 --> 02:16:06.360
long outlasting our short
time within these ivy walls.

02:16:06.360 --> 02:16:08.150
Two verses maybe
not seem like a lot

02:16:08.150 --> 02:16:10.330
to express everything we
have felt during our time

02:16:10.330 --> 02:16:14.000
here, like the refreshing
and liberating feeling

02:16:14.000 --> 02:16:16.620
of the frigid
Cambridge air caressing

02:16:16.620 --> 02:16:20.710
our skin during your first
primal scream and the pain

02:16:20.710 --> 02:16:24.410
in your knees after getting
caught in your first pile up.

02:16:24.410 --> 02:16:27.830
The embarrassment you fell
after walking into Lowell House

02:16:27.830 --> 02:16:32.250
and naively asking, where
is the lecture hall?

02:16:32.250 --> 02:16:35.510
Or the moment you turned in
your thesis simultaneously

02:16:35.510 --> 02:16:38.020
turning [INAUDIBLE].

02:16:38.020 --> 02:16:39.770
But this year's writers
of the class ode

02:16:39.770 --> 02:16:42.510
have done a remarkable
job at representing

02:16:42.510 --> 02:16:46.830
a piece of our college
lives in 124 words.

02:16:46.830 --> 02:16:48.969
We would like to introduce
the writers hailing

02:16:48.969 --> 02:16:50.969
from the Harvard
University band.

02:16:50.969 --> 02:16:53.469
[CHEERS]

02:16:56.859 --> 02:16:59.150
Thank you.

02:16:59.150 --> 02:17:05.690
Allyson Freedy, Sebastian Gomez,
Radhika Jain, Stephen Kent,

02:17:05.690 --> 02:17:09.170
James Looney, and
Georgia Abrantes Shelton

02:17:09.170 --> 02:17:11.739
to present the 2014 class ode.

02:17:11.739 --> 02:17:13.619
[APPLAUSE]

02:17:13.619 --> 02:17:17.540
Please rise now and join us in
performing the class ode sung

02:17:17.540 --> 02:17:19.830
to the tune of Fair Harvard.

02:17:19.830 --> 02:17:22.189
Lyrics can be found
printed in your program.

02:17:36.870 --> 02:17:38.846
[MUSIC]

02:17:45.262 --> 02:17:45.762
[SINGING]

02:17:45.762 --> 02:17:53.790
Come classmates and loved
ones, rejoice on this day.

02:17:53.790 --> 02:17:58.386
Take a breath now that
four years have passed.

02:18:01.150 --> 02:18:08.699
From bright crimson lanyards
to tassels and gowns

02:18:08.699 --> 02:18:13.345
to the futures with
which we've been tasked.

02:18:16.100 --> 02:18:23.730
First housing day nerves,
then storming the yard,

02:18:23.730 --> 02:18:28.014
taming Yale yet again and again.

02:18:30.549 --> 02:18:37.895
All nighters, plans changing,
fears hidden and shared,

02:18:37.895 --> 02:18:45.760
till we stood not
alone but as friends.

02:18:45.760 --> 02:18:53.216
Resolutely we plunged
into erudite toil,

02:18:53.216 --> 02:18:59.870
treasured instincts
of home we soon found.

02:18:59.870 --> 02:19:07.678
Then deadlines they seemed
not to matter at all,

02:19:07.678 --> 02:19:14.510
as we echoed the
strength of this town.

02:19:14.510 --> 02:19:22.420
Fair Harvard so dear,
we cherish with pride.

02:19:22.420 --> 02:19:29.709
Every offset and
triumph we've lived.

02:19:29.709 --> 02:19:36.350
Of science and art and
of courage we learned.

02:19:38.910 --> 02:19:47.366
Now we part to
create and to give.

02:19:47.366 --> 02:19:50.342
[APPLAUSE]

02:20:06.730 --> 02:20:09.590
Thank you very much for
writing our class ode.

02:20:09.590 --> 02:20:11.274
I am thankful to the
Harvard Glee Club

02:20:11.274 --> 02:20:12.690
because I actually
know that tune.

02:20:12.690 --> 02:20:13.980
[LAUGHTER]

02:20:13.980 --> 02:20:14.840
Hey!

02:20:14.840 --> 02:20:15.820
Hey!

02:20:15.820 --> 02:20:19.930
[LAUGHTER]

02:20:19.930 --> 02:20:23.080
Good afternoon, class
of 2014, faculty,

02:20:23.080 --> 02:20:26.076
administrators,
family and friends.

02:20:26.076 --> 02:20:27.450
My name is
Christopher Cleveland,

02:20:27.450 --> 02:20:31.013
and I am proud to serve as
your 2014 second marshal.

02:20:31.013 --> 02:20:33.380
[CHEERS]

02:20:33.380 --> 02:20:37.830
Despite the weather, today
has truly been amazing.

02:20:37.830 --> 02:20:39.460
I want to thank
each of our speakers

02:20:39.460 --> 02:20:42.560
today for sharing
their experiences.

02:20:42.560 --> 02:20:44.920
As I look upon the
yard, I can tell

02:20:44.920 --> 02:20:48.590
that Harvard has touched
each of us in a unique way.

02:20:48.590 --> 02:20:51.830
The inspiration of
convocation, the enormity

02:20:51.830 --> 02:20:56.400
of Harvard's 375th birthday,
the solidarity after the Boston

02:20:56.400 --> 02:21:00.460
Marathon bombing, and the
revelry of Senior Week

02:21:00.460 --> 02:21:03.350
have become the tears and
laughter of remembrance

02:21:03.350 --> 02:21:06.020
as we reflect on
what it has meant

02:21:06.020 --> 02:21:11.370
and means to be a part
of the class of 2014.

02:21:11.370 --> 02:21:14.250
I have come to see the
journey of a Harvard education

02:21:14.250 --> 02:21:18.050
as a transition from feeling
welcome in this place to that

02:21:18.050 --> 02:21:20.640
of belonging in this place.

02:21:20.640 --> 02:21:23.952
And there's a key
difference between the two.

02:21:23.952 --> 02:21:25.790
The realization
of this difference

02:21:25.790 --> 02:21:30.050
came to me as I sat with my
house master, Rakesh Khurana,

02:21:30.050 --> 02:21:34.910
and other students at
a recent breakfast.

02:21:34.910 --> 02:21:37.420
Rakesh looked at
each of us asked

02:21:37.420 --> 02:21:39.660
what sentiments
the word belonging

02:21:39.660 --> 02:21:42.540
raised within each of us.

02:21:42.540 --> 02:21:44.375
We settled on the
feeling of ownership.

02:21:47.260 --> 02:21:50.370
At Harvard, we are not guests.

02:21:50.370 --> 02:21:55.950
We are the owners of this
place, the education, the name,

02:21:55.950 --> 02:21:58.740
and the power.

02:21:58.740 --> 02:22:00.510
Our journey at
Harvard has challenged

02:22:00.510 --> 02:22:03.810
us to think not merely as
visitors to this place,

02:22:03.810 --> 02:22:06.350
but as cultivators
of a university

02:22:06.350 --> 02:22:10.000
that enables the students to
be successful, and encourages

02:22:10.000 --> 02:22:13.010
the success to touch the lives
of people around the world.

02:22:16.200 --> 02:22:18.880
The transition
has been exciting.

02:22:18.880 --> 02:22:21.720
Through our courses and
extracurriculars, friends

02:22:21.720 --> 02:22:24.055
and mentors, we
have been stretched

02:22:24.055 --> 02:22:28.390
to understand ourselves
as Harvard students.

02:22:28.390 --> 02:22:31.990
And the transition has
not always been easy.

02:22:31.990 --> 02:22:35.080
As our student speakers
today have shown us,

02:22:35.080 --> 02:22:36.960
we can all understand
those times

02:22:36.960 --> 02:22:40.852
during our education at
Harvard when we felt crippled,

02:22:40.852 --> 02:22:46.700
when we're sure we've peaked,
when we've experienced love,

02:22:46.700 --> 02:22:50.580
and when we're certain
we have failed.

02:22:50.580 --> 02:22:55.350
And yet, despite the
challenges of this transition,

02:22:55.350 --> 02:23:00.010
we can probably claim
today on Class Day,

02:23:00.010 --> 02:23:05.450
that each and every member
of 2014 belongs at Harvard,

02:23:05.450 --> 02:23:11.240
owns Harvard, and is Harvard.

02:23:11.240 --> 02:23:13.440
As we look toward the
festivities of commencement

02:23:13.440 --> 02:23:16.110
tomorrow, we are
encouraged to carry

02:23:16.110 --> 02:23:19.300
our sense of belonging
to the class of 2014

02:23:19.300 --> 02:23:23.430
and to Harvard College
onward into the beginning

02:23:23.430 --> 02:23:28.080
and throughout our alumni lives.

02:23:28.080 --> 02:23:31.590
Harvard class of 2014, you
have accomplished something

02:23:31.590 --> 02:23:35.110
magnificent by graduating
from the college.

02:23:35.110 --> 02:23:37.000
I look forward to
seeing you all tomorrow

02:23:37.000 --> 02:23:40.780
as we are given our degrees,
and in the coming years

02:23:40.780 --> 02:23:45.570
as we use our degrees to do
amazing things for this world.

02:23:45.570 --> 02:23:48.950
Thank you, and congratulations.

02:23:48.950 --> 02:23:52.000
[APPLAUSE]

